[SourceQuality "1"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3 $5 {A small surprise. Fischer, an inveterate King's
Indian player successfully played the King's Indian Attack back in his youth  
(1 Nf3, then g2-g3, Bg2, d2-d3, Nbd2 and e2-e4), and later he used it to gain
a number of memorable wins – over Ivkov (Santa Monica 1966), Durao (Havana
Olympiad 1966), Miagmarsuren (Sousse Interzonal 1967) and as Black, but with
the same set-up, over E.Nikolic (Vinkovci 1968). In 1970, following Fischer's
example, many young players, including the author of these lines, tried
playing this way.} Nc6 4. g3 g6 5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 7. Re1 d6 ({The
automatic} 7... O-O $5 {allows} 8. e5 (8. c3 e5 $1) 8... d6 9. exd6 Qxd6 10.
Nbd2 Qc7 11. Nb3 Nd4 12. Bf4 Qb6 13. Ne5 Nxb3 $2 (13... Bxe5 {is correct:} 14.
Bxe5 f6 15. Bf4 e5 16. Bh6 Re8 17. Bd2 Be6 {with equality}) 14. Nc4 $1 Qb5 15.
axb3 a5 16. Bd6 Bf6 17. Qf3 Kg7 18. Re4 (18. Qxf6+ $3 {would have won
immediately}) 18... Rd8 {(there is no longer any acceptable defence against
the queen sacrifice)} 19. Qxf6+ $3 Kxf6 20. Be5+ Kg5 21. Bg7 $1 {1-0  
(Petrosian-Pachman, Bled 1961). A delightful miniature!}) 8. c3 O-O ({With the
pawn on c3,} 8... e5 $5 {is logical, with complete equality in the centre:} 9.
Be3 ({or} 9. a3 O-O 10. b4 b6 11. Nbd2 h6 12. Nc4 Be6 13. Ne3 Qd7) 9... O-O 10.
Na3 b6 11. Nc2 d5 {(Schweber-Petrosian, Buenos Aires 1964).}) 9. d4 cxd4 10.
cxd4 d5 ({Black solves his opening problems more easily with the energetic} 
10... Qb6 $1 11. d5 (11. Be3 $6 Qxb2) {, and now} 11... Bxb2 ({or} 11... Nd4
12. Nc3 exd5 {with a comfortable game, Clarke-Kottnauer, Hastings 1968/69}) 12.
Bxb2 Qxb2 13. dxc6 (13. Nbd2 $1 {is better, with compensation for the pawn})
13... Qxa1 14. Qb3 ({if} 14. cxb7 Bxb7 15. Qb3 {, then} Bd5 $1) 14... Nxc6 15.
Nc3 Nd4 $1 16. Rxa1 Nxb3 17. axb3 Bd7 {with equality (Ljubojevic-Hübner,
Buenos Aires Olympiad 1978).}) 11. e5 Bd7 $2 {Inadmissibly passive play,
allowing White to calmly complete his development and retain a spatial
advantage.} ({The centre should have been immediately undermined by} 11... f6
$1 {; for example:} 12. exf6 ({Emms recommended} 12. Bf4 {, but then both} fxe5
({and} 12... Qb6 {with the threat of ...Qxb2 or ...Nf5}) 13. dxe5 h6 {are
satisfactory for Black}) 12... Bxf6 13. Bh6 Re8 14. Nc3 Nf5 {with equality.})
12. Nc3 Rc8 13. Bf4 Na5 14. Rc1 b5 15. b3 b4 16. Ne2 Bb5 ({Little would be
changed by} 16... Rxc1 {(Trifunovic)} 17. Nxc1 Bb5 18. Nd3 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 {
– cf. the following note.}) 17. Qd2 Nac6 18. g4 $1 a5 $6 {Black's
demonstration on the queenside is largely a waste of time, since White is
preparing a typical attack on the kingside.} ({The commentators considered} 
18... Bxe2 19. Qxe2 Qb6 {to be necessary (Trifunovic even recommended this a
move earlier), but then White would have gained the advantage of the two
bishops and could have developed his initiative on both wings.}) 19. Ng3 Qb6
20. h4 Nb8 21. Bh6 $1 ({If} 21. Bg5 {, then} Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Nec6 $1 23. Bf6 (23.
h5 Nd7) 23... h6 {, creating a solid defensive wall: if h4-h5 there follows ...
g6-g5.}) 21... Nd7 22. Qg5 ({The seemingly menacing} 22. Nh5 $6 gxh5 23. Qg5 {
is parried by} Ng6 24. gxh5 ({or} 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 25. gxh5 h6 26. Qg4 Bd3 $1)
24... Rxc1 25. Rxc1 Be2 $5 26. hxg6 fxg6 27. Bxg7 Kxg7 {and ...Bxf3.}) 22...
Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Bxh6 ({Now the undermining move} 23... f6 {would have been far
less effective: after} 24. exf6 Bxh6 (24... Bxf6 25. Qe3) 25. Qxh6 Nxf6 26. Bh3
$1 {White would have retained a strategic initiative, thanks to the weakness
of the e6-pawn and the e5-square.}) 24. Qxh6 Rc8 ({Not} 24... f6 25. h5 $1 {
; Panno endeavours to avoid any sharp advances, relying on the solidity of his
position.}) 25. Rxc8+ Nxc8 26. h5 Qd8 $2 ({Black's difficulties are
picturesquely illustrated by the following possible variations:} 26... Bd3 27.
Bf1 $1 Bxf1 (27... Qb5 28. Ng5 {and N3e4!}) 28. Ng5 Nf8 29. Nxh7 $1 Nxh7 30.
hxg6 fxg6 31. Qxg6+ Kf8 32. Kxf1 Qxd4 33. Qh6+ $1 Ke7 34. Qxh7+ Kd8 35. Qg7 $1
Ne7 (35... Qa1+ 36. Kg2 Qxa2 37. Nf5 $3 exf5 38. e6 {, winning}) 36. Nh5 {
and White should win.}) (26... Qc7 27. Ng5 Nf8 (27... Qc1+ 28. Bf1 Nf8 29. Nxf7
$1) 28. Nxh7 $1 Nxh7 29. hxg6 fxg6 30. Qxg6+ {and Qxe6 with a mass of pawns
and a powerful attack for the piece.}) (26... Nf8 $1 27. Z0 ({, when} 27. Ng5
$2 Qxd4 28. Nxh7 Nxh7 29. hxg6 Nf8 $1 {is bad for White – Emms}) ({. If
instead} 27. Qg5 {, then} Qc7 $1 28. h6 Z0 ({, and now not} 28... Nd7 $2 29.
Nh5 Na7 30. Nh4 $1 Kf8 (30... Qc8 31. Bxd5 $1 exd5 32. e6) 31. Ng7 Qc8 32. Bxd5
$1 exd5 (32... Nc6 33. Nxe6+) 33. e6 fxe6 34. Nxg6+ $1 hxg6 35. Nxe6+ {etc}) ({
, but only} 28... Qe7 $1 {when Black avoids a rout (but not his difficulties
after the moves} 29. Qc1 {and Bf1!).})) ({. White can also look for other
plans (say, with} 27. Bf1 {), but in any case there would still have been a
complicated battle in prospect, whereas the move in the game is refuted by a
knockout blow.})) 27. Ng5 Nf8 28. Be4 $3 {Very spectacular –} ({especially
compared with the stereotyped} 28. Nxh7 $5 Nxh7 29. hxg6 fxg6 30. Qxg6+ Kh8 31.
Qxe6 Ne7 32. f4 {and wins – and, more important, typical of Fischer: despite
everything his favourite bishop switches to an attacking diagonal – the
g6-point begins to creak!}) 28... Qe7 (28... dxe4 {fails to} 29. N3xe4 {
and Nf6+}) ({while if} 28... Be8 {, then} 29. hxg6 hxg6 30. Nh5 $1 gxh5 31.
Bh7+ Nxh7 32. Nxh7 f6 33. Nxf6+ Kf7 34. gxh5 (34. g5 $5) 34... Ke7 35. Qg7+ Bf7
36. h6 Qf8 37. Nxd5+ $1 {etc.}) 29. Nxh7 $1 ({The following computer line
would also have decided:} 29. Nf5 $1 gxf5 (29... exf5 30. gxf5 Qd7 31. Bxd5)
30. gxf5 exf5 31. Bxf5 f6 32. Be6+ $3 Nxe6 33. exf6 {.}) 29... Nxh7 30. hxg6
fxg6 (30... Nf8 31. g7) 31. Bxg6 Ng5 (31... Nf8 32. Nh5) ({or} 31... Qg7 32.
Bxh7+ Qxh7 33. Qxe6+ {was no better.}) 32. Nh5 Nf3+ 33. Kg2 Nh4+ 34. Kg3 Nxg6
35. Nf6+ Kf7 36. Qh7+ 1-0

