1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. d3 e6 4. Nbd2 d5 5. g3 Nf6 6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. Re1
b6 $6 {"This is too passive. In this kind of position where White has the edge
on the kingside and Black on the queenside, it's vital to play as actively as
possible and open lines, diagonals and, if possible, create outposts for the
knights" (Engqvist)} ({More active is} 8... b5) 9. e5 Ne8 $6 {Too passive.} (
9... Nd7) 10. Nf1 Kh8 11. Bf4 f5 12. h4 $1 {[%cal Rg7g5,Rh4g5,Gh4h5]} (12. exf6
Bxf6 13. c3 $14 {[%csl Ye5,Re6][%cal Gf4e5,Gf3e5]}) 12... Nc7 13. N1d2 $1 {
[%csl Rg4][%cal Gd2b3,Rf1h2,Rh2g4,Rf5g4]} Bb7 ({Petrosian gives} 13... d4 $2
14. Nc4 Nd5 15. Bg5 b5 $2 16. Nd6 Nxe5 17. Nxe5 Qxd6 18. Bxd5 {followed by 19
Bxe7 with a won position.}) 14. c3 b5 $6 ({This move should have been replaced
with the central thrust} 14... d4 {[%cal Gc7d5] , as has been suggested by
Ragozin. The main idea is to transfer the knight to d5.}) {Korchnoi once said:
"Against Petrosian, as against no one else, it was dangerous to advance your
pawns..."} 15. Nb3 $1 {The white knight is targeting c5 which was weakened by
Black's last move. White is planning to increase the pressure with Bg5 or Be3.}
a5 16. Bg5 Na6 17. d4 c4 ({Petrosian has analysed the pawn exchange} 17... cxd4
18. cxd4 {as advantageous for White because of the idea of transferring the
b3-knight to d3 via c1. From d3 it controls the important squares c5 and f4.})
({Ragozin's suggestion} 17... h6 {is rebuffed by} 18. Bxe7 Qxe7 19. h5 {
followed by Nh4 with a clear advantage to White.}) 18. Nc1 {[%csl Re6][%cal
Gc1e2,Ge2f4] The knight is heading for f4 via e2, putting pressure on the
other weakness on e6.} Nc7 {Barcza plays passively in this game.} ({More
active is} 18... b4 {.}) 19. Ne2 Kg8 20. Nf4 Qe8 21. Bxe7 Qxe7 22. Ng5 g6 $2 ({
Black needed to secure his pawn chain with} 22... Qd7 {and now White can
exploit the situation.}) 23. a4 $1 Ba6 $2 ({Better is} 23... b4 {, but Black
nevertheless has a tough situation after the forced sequence} 24. Ngxe6 $1 Nxe6
25. Nxd5 Qf7 26. Nf6+ Kg7 27. d5 Nxe5 28. dxe6 Qxf6 29. Bxb7 {with a clear
advantage to White. (Engqvist)}) 24. Nfxe6 $1 ({Also} 24. Ngxe6 $1 Nxe6 25.
Bxd5 Ncd8 26. Bxa8 Nxf4 27. axb5 Bxb5 28. gxf4 {is winning.}) 24... Nxe6 25.
Bxd5 Rad8 26. Bxe6+ Kg7 27. axb5 Bxb5 28. d5 f4 29. Qg4 h6 30. Nh3 1-0

