-40,46,52,40,4,18,28,45,18,33,-13,20,-2,-2,11,15,12,-31,-33,47,75,61,61,76,75,
75,76,70,77,47,57,64,70,60,62,58,66,73,54,54,54,83,29,63,59,75,79,64,37,34,45,
63,74,77,45,33,49,48,26,21,5,18,0,0,-11,0,-15,0,10,5,0]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3.
Bg2 e6 4. O-O Be7 5. d3 O-O 6. Nbd2 c5 7. e4 Nc6 8. e5 Nd7 9. Re1 b5 10. Nf1 a5
11. h4 b4 12. N1h2 Ba6 13. Bf4 Rc8 14. Bh3 ({After} 14. Ng5 Nd4 {Black has
nothing to fear. For example, if} 15. Qh5 $2 h6 16. Ng4 hxg5 17. hxg5 {White
might hope to strike a decisive blow with ideas of Nf6+ or Be4, Kg2 and Rh1.
But this is all a mirage as} g6 $1 {kills off the attack (McDonald)}) ({
The general idea behind} 14. Bh3 {is to put pressure on e6 and introduce the
motif of Ng5 and Nxe6 to destroy Black's centre. Here there is also a more
concrete reason for the bishop move: for example if Black continues pushing
queenside pawns with} a4 {then} 15. Ng5 {suddenly has more potency as} Nd4 16.
c3 Nf5 $2 17. Bxf5 exf5 18. e6 $1 fxe6 19. Nxe6 {wins the exchange.
Brandenburg, therefore, decides on a different defensive plan against White's
attacking idea. First of all, he puts his king on h8 to avoid any Ng5, Nxe6
and Bxe6 idea coming with a check. It is also good to rule out any sacrifice
of a knight on f6 being with a check (McDonald)}) 14... Kh8 15. Ng5 Qe8 $1 {
The only way to meet the threat Qd1-h5!} ({Thus after} 15... Qe8 16. Qh5 Bxg5
17. hxg5 {Black can play} f5 $1 {to gain space and challenge the white queen.
The point is that White can only capture en passant straightaway with} 18. exf6
{, which would normally be great for him as the black centre collapses, but
here} Qxh5 {pockets the queen. But if White plays 18 Qxe8 first, he can't take
with 19 exf6 on the next move, the chance for an en passant capture having
lapsed (McDonald)}) 16. Rc1 Nb6 17. Ng4 Na4 $2 (17... Nd7 $1) 18. Rb1 {Missing
his chance.} ({After} 18. Nf6 $3 gxf6 19. exf6 Bxf6 {Continuing the
combination, White could win with} 20. Qh5 Bxg5 21. Bf5 $3 {(the point; the
threat of mate costs Black the queen)} exf5 22. Bxg5 $1 Qe6 ({if} 22... Qd7 23.
Bf6+ {and mate next move}) 23. Rxe6 fxe6 24. Re1 {. Materially speaking Black
has more than enough for the queen, but the weak dark squares around his king
can be exploited by the white queen and bishop: for example,} Nd4 25. Qh6 Rce8
26. Bf6+ Rxf6 27. Qxf6+ Kg8 28. h5 {(McDonald)}) ({Going back to move 18, also
inadequate for Black is} 18. Nf6 Bxf6 19. exf6 gxf6 20. Qh5 fxg5 21. Bf5 exf5
22. Rxe8 Rcxe8 23. Bd6 Rg8 ({if} 23... Ne7 24. Bxe7 Rxe7 25. Qh6 {attacks a6
and f8, and has ideas of 26 Qf6+ winning the rook on e7}) 24. Qxf7 Nd4 25. Qf6+
Rg7 26. Bf8 {and White wins. Of course, it would have been extraordinarily
difficult to have seen this combination. Even if White had spotted the tactic
21 Bf5!! he would have had to convince himself that Black was in trouble
despite having a rook and two minor pieces for the queen (McDonald)}) 18... c4
19. dxc4 Bxc4 20. Ne3 ({Here was the last chance for} 20. Nf6 $1 {which is
similar to 18 Nf6.}) 20... Nc5 21. Nxc4 dxc4 22. Qh5 Bxg5 23. Bxg5 Nd4 24. Qd1
Qd7 25. c3 Nc6 26. Qd6 Qxd6 27. exd6 h6 28. cxb4 axb4 29. Be3 Nd3 30. Red1 Rfd8
31. b3 Rxd6 32. bxc4 Nce5 33. c5 Rd7 34. Bf1 Nxc5 35. Rdc1 Rdc7 36. Rxb4 Ned3
37. Bxd3 Nxd3 38. Rxc7 Rxc7 39. Rb8+ Kh7 40. a4 Rc4 41. Rb3 Nb4 42. a5 Nc2 43.
Bd2 Ra4 44. Kg2 Ra2 45. Rb7 Kg8 46. Ra7 Nd4 47. Bc3 Nb5 48. Ra8+ Kh7 49. Be1
Kg6 50. g4 h5 51. Rb8 Nd4 52. Bc3 e5 53. g5 f6 54. gxf6 gxf6 55. Bxd4 1/2-1/2

