1. e4 e6 2. d3 d5 3. Nd2 Nf6 4. Ngf3 b6 5. c3 Be7 6. Qa4+ Qd7 7. Qc2 O-O (7...
c5 8. e5 Ng8 9. d4 Ba6 10. Bxa6 Nxa6 11. O-O Nh6 12. Re1 O-O 13. Nf1 Nf5 14.
Qe2 Nc7 15. Ng3 Nxg3 16. hxg3 cxd4 17. Nxd4 Bc5 18. Be3 f6 19. exf6 Rxf6 20.
Bg5 Rg6 21. Bf4 Rf8 22. Be5 Ne8 23. Rad1 Nf6 24. b4 Bxd4 25. Rxd4 Qe7 26. Rf4
Ne4 27. c4 Rg5 28. Rxf8+ Qxf8 29. Bf4 Rg6 30. cxd5 Nc3 31. Qa6 Nxd5 32. Rc1
Qxb4 33. Rc8+ Kf7 34. Qxa7+ Kf6 35. Qb8 Nxf4 36. Rf8+ Kg5 37. Qe5+ Kh6 38. Rxf4
Qb1+ 39. Kh2 Rg5 40. Rh4+ {1-0 Iordachescu,V (2500)-Baklan,V (2570)/Zagan 1997/
CBM 059 ext}) 8. e5 Ne8 9. d4 Ba6 10. h4 f5 11. exf6 gxf6 12. Bxa6 Nxa6 13. Qd3
Nb8 14. Nf1 c5 15. Bh6 Rf7 16. O-O-O Nc6 17. Ne3 c4 18. Qe2 b5 19. Rh3 b4 20.
Rg3+ Kh8 {Diagram [#]} 21. Ne5 $5 {Clearence. White opens a road for the queen.
} Nxe5 $2 {Black collapses under pressure. His best defensive resource was:} (
21... fxe5 22. Qg4 Bg5 $8 {[%cal Rd7g7,Rf7g7,Re8g7,Ra8g8] Counter-clearence.
Black can now safely cover the vital g7 square.} (22... Nf6 $4 23. Bg7+ Kg8 24.
Bxf6+ Kf8 25. Qg8#) 23. Qxg5 Nd6 (23... Nf6 {is also possible, although White
may try to use the pin after:} 24. Bg7+ Rxg7 25. Qxf6 bxc3 26. bxc3 exd4 27.
Nxd5 {[%cal Rf6c6]} exd5 28. Rxg7 Qxg7 29. Qxc6 $13 {White's king looks unsafe,
but Black's pawns are dropping down.}) 24. f3 Nb5 $132) 22. dxe5 f5 $2 (22...
Bf8 $142 23. Qg4 Bg7 24. exf6 Nxf6 25. Bxg7+ Rxg7 26. Qxg7+ Qxg7 27. Rxg7 Kxg7
28. cxb4 {nets a pawn for White, but Black has a strong central pawn chain.})
23. Nxd5 {[%cal Re5e6,Re6d7,Re6f7] using the fork motives White breaks through.
} Qb5 24. Qh5 Qb7 25. Nf4 bxc3 {Now small combination on clearence comes again.
} 26. Ng6+ (26. Ng6+ hxg6 (26... Kg8 27. Nxe7+ Kh8 28. Rg8#) 27. Bg7+ {
deflection} Kxg7 28. Rxg6+ Kf8 29. Qh8#) 1-0

