1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4
d6 9. b3 {We will start by invesigating the systems with double fianchetto.
Among these, we will first examine the cases when White provokes the exchange
of the light-squared bishops. True, this usually happens after Nxd4, but in
the first game the knight will move to the centre a bit later than usual.} O-O
10. Rd1 Nbd7 11. Bb2 a6 12. Qe3 $5 $146 {At that time, a new move.} (12. e4 {
(or 13.e4 after, say, Rac1) used to be the main continuation and it remains
the most popular one up to today.}) 12... Qb8 $6 {This slightly extravagant
move plans the quick major piece regrouping to the queenside. In this position,
it fails to anticipate White?s intentions.} (12... Qc7 {is more natural and
better.} 13. Nd4 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Rfe8 (14... Rab8 $11 {Gulko} 15. Nf5 $1 $16) 15.
Rac1 Rac8 {White's main plan is advancing the f-and g-pawns, while leaving the
e-pawn on either e2 or e3. With queens on board, this is not easy to achieve.}
16. Kg1 {Clearing space for the queen.} (16. Qf3 Ne5) 16... Bf8 17. Qf3 (17. f4
$6 e5 $1 {yields Black dangerous initiative in the centre.}) 17... Ne5 18. Qg2
Qb8 19. h3 (19. f4 $6 Neg4 20. Qf3 e5) 19... Rc5 $5 {Preparing ...b6-b5.} 20.
Ba3 {Crossing Black's plans, but misplacing the bishop slightly.} (20. g4 b5)
20... Rc7 21. g4 h6 22. e3 Ng6 {We can see that White cannot make progress
easily.}) 13. Nd4 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 {We can see the second important element in
Karpov's plan. The knight's intursion to c6 is a real threat now.} Qb7+ {
This plays into White's hands. Without queens on board, White will be able to
cary out the kingside plan at leisure. However, it is not easy to find an
optimal antidote to the threat Nc6.} (14... Rc8 {leaves the kingside
vulnerable, making} 15. f4 {playable. WHite will continue with Qf3, continuing
to target c6 and g3-g4-g5.}) (14... Ng4 15. Qf4 Nge5 {also leaves Black's
pieces slightly unusually placed.}) 15. Qf3 $1 Qxf3+ 16. Nxf3 Rfc8 17. Nd4 Rab8
18. Rac1 $14 h6 {White has completed his development and should choose the
plan for the queenless middlegame.} 19. e4 $6 {This is not part of the plan
indicated earlier. As mentioned then, White should aim for the structure with
pawns on e3, f4 and g5 (after the insertion of h2-h4). This would be similar
to the queenside attack based on b2-b4-b5 in the English Opening with a bishop
on g2. With the black king in the targeted area, things may be even more
dangerous for Black than in the English opening. The opening of a file would
have heavy consequences while if Black manages to keep the position closed,
his king will be under permanent pressure, even in the endgame. We can compare
with certain Richter Rauzer Sicilian positions, when the black pawns on a4 and
b4 keep the white king passive, while also creating some concrete dangers.} (
19. f4 $5 Ng4 20. Rd2 {followed by h2-h3 and so on.}) (19. h3 $5 Nc5 20. f4 {
Otherwise, Kf3 followed by g3-g4 qnd h3-h4.} Nce4 21. Kf3 Nxc3 22. Bxc3 {
White's plan still remains valid. The only chane for black activity is} b5 {
, but this is likely to backfire.} 23. cxb5 axb5 24. Bb4 Rxc1 (24... Bf8 25.
Nc6 {wins the pawn on d6 since} Rb6 $2 26. Ne7+ {wins the exchange.}) 25. Rxc1
{The same as in the line above, the control over the c-file in general and the
c6-square in particular yield White a clear advatage.} Bf8 26. f5 e5 27. Nc6
Ra8 28. Rc2 g6 29. g4 $16) 19... Ne8 $6 {Too passive.} (19... Ne5 {/\ Nc6, b5
Gulko This does not seem to spare Black problems.} 20. f4 Nc6 21. Nxc6 Rxc6 22.
Kf3 b5 $6 23. cxb5 axb5 24. e5 $1 dxe5 25. fxe5 Ne8 26. Nd5 $1 Rxc1 27. Nxe7+
Kf8 28. Bxc1 Kxe7 29. a4 $16 {The king is in danger in view of the potenatial
possibility of Ba3+.} b4 $6 30. Be3 $18) (19... Nc5 $1 {was the right reaction.
} 20. f3 g5 $1 {Since White failed to advance his pawns properly, Black can
turn them into weaknesses. The main threat is ...g5-g4.} 21. h3 h5 $132) 20. f4
Bf6 21. Kf3 Rb7 (21... Kf8 $1 {(/\ Ke7)} 22. e5 $2 dxe5 23. Nxe6+ Ke7 $17 {
Gulko WHite is not forced to break in the centre and can continue along
Karpov's plan in the game.}) 22. Ba3 $1 Rbc7 {Threatening ...b6-b5, due to the
pin along the c-file.} 23. Nce2 $1 {The start of a global regrouping.
Apparently, White only parries the threat, but there is more about it.} Nc5 24.
Rd2 $5 {ANother typical move for Karpov. With this placement, the rooks can
collaborate in various ways. WHite can double them along the d- or c-file, or
else he can keep the d-file under control and transfer the other rook to, say,
g1.} g6 25. Nc2 $1 {Another mysterious move.} Bg7 26. Ne3 {This is the
regrouping intended by Karpov. The knights control all the important squares
along the c-file (for the case Black manages to break with ...b6-b5) and
collaborate with the pawns for a consistent kingside attack.} f5 {Black
finally understands the danger and tries to fight back on the kingside.} (26...
b5 27. cxb5 axb5 28. Rdc2 {As we can see, Rd2 made a lot of sense.} Bf8 29. Nd4
Rb8 30. b4 Na6 31. Nc6 Ra8 32. Bb2 Nc5 $5 33. Na5 {with stable advantage for
White.}) 27. exf5 gxf5 28. h3 {This allows Black to get rid of his potentially
weak h-pawn.} (28. g4 fxg4+ 29. Nxg4 {was worth considering.}) 28... h5 29. Rg1
Rf7 30. g4 hxg4+ 31. hxg4 fxg4+ 32. Rxg4 Kf8 33. Ng3 {Even so, White's
pressure remains annoying.} a5 (33... Ke7 34. Rg6 Rf6 {- Gulko} 35. Rxf6 $1
Nxf6 (35... Bxf6 36. Rh2 $14) 36. Ngf5+ exf5 37. Nxf5+ Kf8 38. Rxd6 $16) 34.
Rg6 Ke7 $2 (34... Rf6 $1 35. Rxg7 Kxg7 (35... Nxg7 36. Rxd6 $16 Rb8 $2 37. Rxb6
) 36. Nh5+ Kg6 37. Nxf6 Kxf6 38. Rh2 $14) 35. f5 $1 Rf6 36. Rxf6 Nxf6 37. Re2
$1 Rf8 $2 (37... e5 38. Bxc5 bxc5 39. Rh2 {with perfect control on the light
squares.}) 38. Bxc5 bxc5 39. fxe6 Kxe6 40. Nef5+ (40. Nef5+ Kf7 41. Re7+) 1-0

