1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 c5 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. b3 {12 years
later, Karpov carried out the same plan with a different move order.} d6 ({
In my Hedgehog repertoire database, I have recommended} 7... Be7 {, delaying ..
.d7-d6. This way, Black gains a tempo for regrouping and does not weaken c6
too soon.} 8. Bb2 O-O 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qc7 12. e3 Nc6 13. Nxc6
Qxc6+ 14. Qf3 Rfc8) 8. Bb2 Be7 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qc7 12. e3 {
We can see that White achieves the desired regrouping quicker than in the
rpevious game.} Qb7+ {Otherwise, f2-f4 followed by Qf3 would leave Black with
constant problems on c6.} 13. Qf3 $18 Ra7 14. Qxb7 Rxb7 15. f4 O-O (15... Nbd7
16. Kf3 (16. Rad1 $14 {Zaitsev}) 16... h5 17. Rad1 {Marin}) 16. f5 $6 {Now is
a good moment to launch a serious warning. With the bishop on b2, the naural
break with f4-f5 is almost always bad. After ...e6-e5 White gets, indeed, the
d5-square for his knights, but the bishop on b2 remains passive.} (16. Kf3 $1
$16 {is examined in the next game.}) 16... e5 $1 17. Nc2 Nc6 $1 {An accurate
answer.} (17... Nbd7 18. Nb4 $16 {would allow White to solve all his problems
of coordination. The bishop could later go to a3.}) 18. Rad1 b5 19. cxb5 axb5
20. b4 {Sad necessity, retsricting the bishop on b2.} Rd8 21. Nd5 Nxd5 22. Rxd5
{White has invaded the critical square, but does not have enough resources to
maintain it under control. His bishop and knight are passive.} Bf6 $6 (22...
Bf8 $1 {is the best way of preparing the central break. The immediate threat
is ...Ne7.} 23. e4 f6 24. Rfd1 Ne7 $1 25. Rxd6 (25. R5d3 d5 26. exd5 Nxf5 27.
g4 Nd6 $17 {Black has the better structure and a perfect blockade on d6.})
25... Rxd6 26. Rxd6 Nxf5 27. Rc6 Nd6 28. Kf3 Nc4 {with excellent play.}) 23.
Rfd1 Ne7 24. Rxd6 Rxd6 25. Rxd6 Nxf5 {The difference now is that the bishop on
f6 is passive and the white bishop exerts real pressure on e5.} 26. Rc6 (26.
Rd5 $1 {was better, keeping Black's weaknesses under pressure.} Rb8 (26... Rc7
27. Rc5 Rxc5 28. bxc5 Ne7 29. Na3 {As we see, White's minor pieces are
suddenly active.}) 27. Bxe5 $5 (27. Kf2 {is an important alternative, slowly
improving the position.}) 27... Rc8 $1 28. Bxf6 Rxc2+ 29. Kf3 gxf6 30. Rxf5
Rxh2 31. a3 Ra2 32. Rxf6 Rxa3 33. Rf5 $16) 26... h5 27. e4 Nd4 28. Rc8+ Kh7 29.
Ne3 Ne6 30. Nd5 Ng5 31. Nc3 Ne6 32. h4 g6 33. Nd5 Bg7 34. Rc6 g5 35. hxg5 Nxg5
36. Nc3 Ne6 37. Nd5 Ng5 38. Rc7 Rxc7 39. Nxc7 Nxe4 40. Nxb5 Bf8 41. Nc3 Nxc3
42. Bxc3 Kg6 43. a4 1-0

