1. Nf3 e6 2. c4 b6 3. g3 Bb7 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. O-O c5 6. Nc3 Be7 7. b3 d6 8. Bb2 a6
9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Bxg2 11. Kxg2 Qc7 12. e3 Qb7+ 13. Qf3 Ra7 14. Qxb7 Rxb7 15.
f4 O-O {By the time this game was played, the best plan for White (in all kind
of similar positions) had been revealed.} 16. Kf3 $1 Rc8 17. Rac1 {A natural
developing move, but White could have started his kingside plan at once.} (17.
g4 Nc6 18. Nxc6 Rxc6 19. g5 Nd7 20. Ne2 b5 21. cxb5 axb5 22. Rfc1 Rbc7 23. Rxc6
Rxc6 24. Nd4 Rb6 25. Rc1 $16) 17... Nc6 {In view of the threat g4-g5, Black
needs the d7-square for his king's knight. Besides, the last move partly
solves the problems with the square on c6 and makes ...b6-b5 a realistic plan.}
18. Nxc6 Rxc6 19. Ne2 {The reserve knight is heading for d4.} Nd7 20. Nd4 Rc8
21. Rfd1 Nc5 22. g4 $14 {WHite has a stable advantage already. Black's attempt
at reaching counterplay only makes things worse.} e5 $6 23. Nf5 e4+ 24. Ke2 Nd3
{This was Black's idea, but it should not have been good enough to compensate
for the numerous weaknesses. First of all, the pawn on e4 is vulnerable to Ng3.
} 25. Rb1 d5 (25... Nxb2 26. Rxb2 {would soon win either the d6 or the e4-pawn.
}) 26. cxd5 $2 {Unnecessarily opening the c-file without a fight, while also
wasting a tempo.} (26. Bxg7 $1 dxc4 27. bxc4 Rxc4 28. Bd4 $16 {[%cal Gf5g3]
Threatening Ng3. The main difference with respect to the game is that the
b-file is open. For this reasons,} Bb4 $2 {does not work.} 29. Rxd3 $1 {
Based on a few tricks involving the knight's vivacity.} exd3+ (29... Rc2+ 30.
Kd1 {leaves the bishop on b4 hanging.}) 30. Kxd3 Rbc7 (30... b5 31. Rxb4 Rxb4
32. Nh6+ Kf8 33. Bc5+) 31. Be5 R7c5 (31... R7c6 32. Rxb4 Rxb4 33. Ne7+) (31...
Rc8 {offers White a chance between the same mechanism as in the previous line
and} 32. Rxb4 Rxb4 33. Nh6+ Kf8 34. Bd6+ Kg7 35. Nf5+ Kf6 36. Bxb4 $18) 32.
Ne7+ Kf8 33. Nd5 Ba5 34. Bd6+ Kg7 35. Bxc5 Rxc5 36. Nxb6 $18) 26... Bb4 $1 {
Black has good counterplay now.} 27. Rxd3 $2 (27. Bxg7 Rc2+ 28. Kf1 h5 $13)
27... Rc2+ $19 28. Rd2 Rxd2+ 29. Kf1 Rc7 30. d6 Rcc2 31. Bd4 Rf2+ 32. Kg1 Rg2+
33. Kh1 Rxh2+ 34. Kg1 Rhg2+ 35. Kh1 Rh2+ 36. Kg1 Rcg2+ 37. Kf1 Rxa2 38. Kg1
Rag2+ 39. Kf1 Rf2+ 40. Kg1 Rfg2+ 41. Kf1 {In conclusion, the plan based on Bb2
and exchanging the other bishop offer White chances for an advantage if Black
does not choose the optimal opening move order. Even if Black does so, then
there are no big risks for White.} 1/2-1/2

