1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 b6 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O e6 6. Nc3 Be7 {We will now
start investigating the plans based on Bb2 and e2-e4, preventing the bishops'
exchange along the light diagonal. This offers White certain harmony and
flexibility, without the risk of reaching a dead end. On the other hand, it
puts no immediate pressure on Black. Since in all the remaining games White
will not allow the exchange of the light-squared bishops, now is a good moment
to give a draft evaluation of the English Hedgehog positions. Apart from the
obvious facts that White has more space and Black is solid and flexible, we
should underline that there is no refutation of this opening. Manoeuvres tend
to be long and slow and the essential thing for both sides is to remain alert
to the opponent's eventual inaccuracies. When one feels that something is
wrong with the opponent's regrouping, one should act at once, as there might
be no second opportunity. This is the secret of the Hedgehog: to care about
the own regrouping and harmony and wait for a favourable moment for striking.}
7. Qc2 $5 {An accelerated way of preparing e2-e4.} O-O ({Black could have
avoided the later slight problems with the development by speeding up the
queenside development.} 7... a6 8. e4 d6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 Qc7) 8. e4 d6 9.
d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4 {The threat e4-e5 causes some problems.} Nbd7 (10... a6 $2 11.
e5 $1 Bxg2 12. exf6 Bxf6 13. Kxg2 Bxd4 14. Qe4 $1 Bxc3 15. Qxa8 $16) (10... Qc7
$5 11. Ncb5 (11. Ndb5 Qxc4) (11. b3 a6) 11... Qc8 12. b3 a6 13. Nc3 Nbd7) 11.
Rd1 (11. e5 Bxg2 12. exf6 Bxf6 {is fine, since the rook on a8 is defended.})
11... Qb8 {The simplest way out of the temporary problems, but once again I am
not enthusiastic about this way of dveeloping the queen.} (11... a6 $2 12. e5 {
and the knight on d4 is defended.}) (11... Qc7 $5 12. Ndb5 Qb8 13. Bf4 Ne5 14.
b3 a6 15. Nd4 Qc7 {leads to a normal position.}) 12. b3 Rc8 {Black starts
approaching the border of acceptable experimenting.} (12... a6 $5 {followed by
...Qc7.}) 13. Bb2 a6 14. Qe2 Ne5 15. Rac1 Nc6 16. Na4 $5 {Being perfectly
mobilised, White creates the first direct threat.} Nd7 $2 {This natural move
loses by force.} (16... Qc7 {was necessary, even though it looks a bit scary
in view of} 17. Nb5 {If White does not play this, the position remains typical
for the slow hedgehog scenario. When commenting his games, Smyslov usually
tries to prove an advantage for him even after the opponent's better moves in
the critical moment. In this case, he just gives a similar evaluation as mine
in the previous sentence.} axb5 18. cxb5 Nd7 19. bxc6 Bxc6 20. Nc3 Qb8 21. a4
Nc5 22. Nd5 $5 exd5 23. exd5 Bxa4 24. Qxe7 {Threatening Qg5.} f6 $1 {
Threatening to trap the queen with ...Re8.} 25. Qe2 Bxb3 $13) 17. Nxe6 $1 $18 {
A typical combination, taking advantage of the black pieces' congestion far
from the own king. As we will see, even the knight on a4 will play an
important part. The variations below are given by Smyslov.} fxe6 18. Qg4 Nf6 (
18... Nde5 19. Qxe6+ Nf7 20. Nxb6 Re8 21. Qg4 Nce5 22. Qe2 Ra7 23. Bd4 Bc6 24.
Nd5 Rb7 25. f4 $18) (18... Kf7 19. Qxg7+ Ke8 20. Qg8+ Nf8 21. Nxb6 $18) 19.
Qxe6+ Kh8 20. Nxb6 Rf8 $5 21. c5 $1 (21. Nxa8 Bc8 $1 {traps the queen.}) 21...
Ra7 (21... dxc5 22. e5 Nd4 23. Bxd4 Bxg2 24. Qxe7 Ng8 (24... Ra7 25. Qxc5 Ne4
26. Qxf8+ Qxf8 27. Rc8 Qxc8 28. Nxc8) 25. Qxc5 Qb7 26. e6 Bh1 27. Bxg7+ Kxg7
28. Rd7+) 22. cxd6 Bd8 23. Na4 Re8 24. Qf7 Ba8 25. d7 Rg8 26. Qe6 Qb5 1-0

