1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 c5 3. Nf3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O d6 7. b3 Be7 8. d4
cxd4 9. Qxd4 a6 {It is interesting to see that Karpov was by far less alert
than Smyslov to such a favourable occasion.} 10. Ba3 O-O 11. Rfd1 Ne8 12. Bb2
Nd7 13. e4 {Once again, WHite has managed to induce some lack of cordination
into Black's army (...Ne8) This is a temporary problem only, though.} Nc5 14.
Qe3 Qb8 (14... Qc7 $5 {[%cal Ga8d8] followed by ...Rd8}) 15. Nd4 Nf6 16. h3 Rc8
17. g4 h6 18. f4 Nh7 19. Qf2 {White obviously prepares h3-h4 followed by g4-g5.
} Ra7 (19... Nf6 $5 20. Qe2 (20. Re1 $2 Nd3) 20... Nh7 $11 {leaves White with
problems advancing the h-pawn.}) 20. Rd2 {The familiar rook lift, preparing to
develop the other rook.} Ba8 {I must admit that there is certain harmony in
Black's position, even though his regrouping is a bit exotic. Time has come
for White to complete his own regrouping in the most effective way.} 21. Re1 $6
{This is natural, but does not take measures against the queenside counterplay.
} (21. h4 $6 b5 22. cxb5 axb5 23. Ndxb5 Ra5 24. Nd4 Nf6 25. Qe2 d5 26. exd5
Qxf4) (21. Rad1 $1 {For hidden reasons, escaping Karpov's fine positional
sense, this would have been the most effective way of keeping things under
control.} b5 (21... Nf6 {can be met with} 22. Re2 {since d3 is defended.} Nh7
23. h4) 22. cxb5 axb5 23. Ndxb5 Rxa2 {The same operation as recommended below,
but under unfavourable circumstances this time.} 24. Nxd6 $1 Bxd6 (24... Rxb2
25. Nxc8 $18) 25. Nxa2 $16) 21... Bf6 $2 {Missing his chance.} (21... b5 $1 22.
cxb5 axb5 23. Ndxb5 Rxa2 $1 24. Nxa2 (24. Nxd6 {fails to} Rxb2 {the secret
being that after} 25. Nxc8 {the rook on d2 is hanging after} Bh4 $1 26. Qxh4
Rxd2 {By coincidence, the rook now defends d8.} 27. Nd5 g5 {White may not be
able to prove his compensation for the lost material.}) 24... Qxb5 {If Black
manages to take on b3 and maintain his knight on c5, he will have full
compensation for the exchange.} 25. Nc1 $5 e5 $5 {Keeping the knight on the
board.} 26. fxe5 (26. f5 $2 Ng5 27. Rde2 Ncxe4 28. Rxe4 {Necessary, since h3
is hanging.} Bxe4 29. Rxe4 Nxe4 30. Bxe4 d5 {[%cal Ge7c5] Threatening ...Bc5.}
31. Bd3 Rxc1+ $1 32. Bxc1 Qxd3 $19) 26... dxe5 {[%cal Gc5e6] Planning to
invade the dark squares starting with ...Ne6.} 27. Bxe5 Nxb3 28. Nxb3 Qxe5 {
With fantastic play on dark squares, compensating for the exchange.}) 22. h4 $1
g5 $2 {This thematical move, fighting for the dark squares, should have led to
disaster.} (22... b5 23. cxb5 (23. g5 hxg5 24. hxg5 Bxd4 25. Qxd4 e5 $5) 23...
axb5 24. b4 Na4 25. Nxa4 Rxa4 26. a3 $16) (22... g6 23. g5 hxg5 24. hxg5 Bg7
25. Re3 {Planning Rh3 and Qh4 with a decisive attack.} e5 26. Nf5 $1 gxf5 27.
exf5 {with a winning attack.}) 23. hxg5 $2 {Karpov reacts feebly and soon
lands in a bad position.} (23. Nd5 $1 {was the right way to take advantage of
the remoteness of many black pieces from the weakened kingside.} exd5 (23...
Bg7 {does not change much} 24. fxg5 hxg5 25. hxg5 {Threatening Nf6, which
could follow as an answer to ...Nxg5, too.} exd5 26. exd5 Re8 27. Rxe8+ Qxe8
28. Nf5 Bxb2 29. Rxb2 {with a decisive attack.}) 24. exd5 Re8 25. Nf5 Bxb2 26.
Rxb2 {The bishop on a8 does not count as an extra piece and the rook on a7 is
also hard to use for defensive purposes. White's attack is decisive.} gxf4 (
26... Rxe1+ 27. Qxe1 Qf8 28. Re2 Nf6 29. fxg5 hxg5 30. hxg5 $18) 27. Rxe8+ Qxe8
28. Re2 Qf8 29. Qxf4 $18) 23... hxg5 24. fxg5 Bxg5 {Black is comfortable now.}
25. Rdd1 Nd7 26. Rd3 Ne5 27. Rh3 Re8 28. Nce2 Rc7 29. a4 Qd8 30. Qg3 Ng6 31.
Qh2 f6 32. Rd1 Rg7 33. Nf3 Bxe4 34. Rxd6 Qc7 35. Ba3 Be3+ 36. Kf1 Bc5 37. Bxc5
Qxc5 38. Rd4 Bxf3 39. Rxf3 Ne5 40. Rh3 Nxg4 41. Qd6 Qf5+ 42. Rf3 Qb1+ 43. Rd1
Qe4 44. Rg3 Ne3+ 45. Kg1 Nxg2 46. Rxg7+ Kxg7 47. Ng3 Qa8 48. Qc7+ Kh8 49. Rd7
Nf8 $2 (49... Ng5 $19) 50. Nf5 $1 {A lucky win by Karpov.} (50. Nf5 exf5 51.
Qh2+ Kg8 52. Qg3+) 1-0

