{This game is illustrative for the way White can deal with a position where
Black has achieved at least part of his dream.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6
4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. d4 cxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. Rd1 a6 10. e4 Nbd7 11.
Qe3 O-O 12. Nd4 Qc7 13. b3 Rfe8 14. Bb2 Bf8 15. Rac1 Rac8 16. h3 Qb8 17. Re1 g6
18. Rcd1 Nc5 19. f3 Bg7 20. Ba1 Ncd7 21. f4 e5 {AFter this move, Black does
not have any problem at all.} 22. Nc2 exf4 ({In my electronic book on the
Hedgehog repertoire, I have examined my game against Gulko, where I managed to
carry out all Black's thematic pawn moves, ...h7-h5, ...e6-e5, ...b6-b5 and ...
d6-d5. In order to achieve full suv=ccess, Black frequently needs to use at
least two of them.} 22... b5 $1 23. cxb5 axb5 $15) 23. Qxf4 Ne5 (23... b5 $5)
24. Nb4 {White has managed to regroup properly and can dream of invading the
c6-square. In the event of ...b6-b5, the b4-knights would blokc the b5-pawn
properly.} h5 25. Rf1 Qc7 26. Kh1 Re6 27. Qd2 Rce8 28. Ncd5 {Facing Black with
certain problems already.} (28. Rf2 $5) 28... Nxd5 29. cxd5 $1 {A paradoxic
move, leaving Black with a perfect blocking knight on e5, but opening the
c-file for White's rook.} (29. exd5 R6e7 {[%cal Gf7f5] followed by ...f7-f5
yields Black fantastic play.}) 29... Rf6 {More or less forced.} (29... R6e7 {
leaves Black congested and exposed to the plan} 30. Rc1 Qd8 31. Bd4 a5 32. Nc6
Bxc6 33. dxc6 Qc7 34. Be3 {followed by Qd5 with certain domination.}) 30. Rf4
$1 {A strong positional exchange sacrifice. After exchaning a rook, the
aforementioned plan does not work so well:} (30. Rc1 Rxf1+ 31. Bxf1 Qe7 32. Nc6
Bxc6 (32... Qd7 $5 $11) 33. dxc6 b5 34. Qd5 Rc8 $13) (30. Rxf6 Bxf6 31. Rc1 Qd8
$5 32. Nc6 Bxc6 33. dxc6 Bg5 $1 34. c7 Bxd2 35. cxd8=Q Rxd8 36. Rd1 Bg5 $11)
30... Rxf4 $2 {Equivalent to surrendering.} (30... Bh6 $1 {was absolutely
necessary. Black needs some material compensation for his positional probglems.
} 31. Qf2 Bxf4 32. gxf4 {Threatening Qg3 with a win.} a5 $1 {Forcing White to
give up a pawn and clear some space for Black's pieces.} (32... g5 $2 33. Qg3
Rxf4 34. Qxg5+ Ng6 35. Qh6 Re5 36. Bxe5 dxe5 37. Nd3 Qc2 38. Qxh5 $18) 33. Nc6
(33. Nd3 $2 Nxd3 34. Rxd3 Qc1+) (33. Nc2 $2 g5 $1 34. Qg3 Qxc2) 33... Bxc6 34.
dxc6 Qxc6 35. Qd2 Rfe6 $5 36. fxe5 dxe5 {Black has a rook and two pawns for
two bishops and his rooks are relatively active. The position remains unclear.}
) 31. gxf4 Nd7 32. Bxg7 Kxg7 33. Nc6 Kg8 34. e5 $18 Kh7 35. Rc1 dxe5 36. Nxe5
Qd6 37. Nxf7 Qf6 38. Ng5+ Kg8 39. Rc7 Nc5 40. b4 Qd6 41. Rf7 1-0

