{We will now switch to positions where White develops his bishop to e3. For
short-term purposes, this is a more active move. It does not waste a tempo on
b2-b3 and it puts indirect pressure on b6, allowing additional tactical tricks.
On the other hand, the bishop is likely to stay in the other pieces' way if
Black manages to parry the early threats. This could lead to a situation where
White has reached a dead end, allowing Black to build up his counterplay. The
first positional threat we will be dealing with is e4-e5.} 1. Nf3 c5 2. c4 Nf6
3. Nc3 e6 4. g3 b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O a6 7. Re1 Be7 8. e4 d6 9. d4 cxd4 10. Nxd4
Qc7 11. Be3 O-O 12. Rc1 Re8 13. f4 Bf8 14. Bf2 Nbd7 15. Qe2 {The first
critical moment. White obviously threatens e4-e5 and Black should find a way
of re-routing his knight on f6.} g6 $2 {This weakens the square on g7 and
forces the knight to go on a passive route.} ({I will once again refer to my
game with Gulko, available in my article on the Hedgehog Repertoire for Black.
On that occasion I played} 15... h5 {, even though this implied sacrificing a
pawn. Black intends to continue with ...g7-g6 and ...e6-e5, taking advantage
of the fact that} 16. e5 $2 dxe5 17. fxe5 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 {allows} Ng4 19. Nf3
Rac8 {with fantastic play.}) (15... h6 {is also possible, clearing the
h7-square foe the knight.} 16. e5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 dxe5 18. fxe5 Nh7 19. h4 Rac8
20. b3 Bb4 {[%cal Gh7f8,Gf8g6,Rf7f6] Black can re-route his knight to g6, or
if White plays ...h4-h5 in the last moment, back to h7-g5.}) 16. e5 $1 {
Not giving Black the time to play ...e6-e5.} Bxg2 17. Kxg2 dxe5 18. fxe5 Nh5
19. b3 Rac8 20. Nf3 {White has a stable advantage now.} Red8 (20... f5 $5 $16)
21. Bd4 Bc5 22. Red1 Bxd4 23. Rxd4 Nb8 {Now is the second critical moment.
Black intends to transfer the knight to c6, but his offers White a free tempo.}
24. Rcd1 $6 {In such positions, it is important to exchange a rook in order to
avoid Black's counterplay along the d-file, but to keep the other, in order to
create strong threats of one's own.} (24. Rxd8+ $1 Qxd8 (24... Rxd8 25. Qe3 Ng7
26. g4 {followed by Qh6 and Ng5}) 25. Qe3 Nd7 26. Rd1 $1 {Preventing ...Qf8
and maintaining the attack.}) 24... Rxd4 25. Rxd4 Nc6 26. Rd2 Ng7 27. g4 $1 {
Preventing ...Nf5 and keeping the knight on the unfavourable path.} Ne8 28. Qe3
Kg7 29. Ne4 Rd8 (29... Nxe5 30. Qd4 f6 31. Nxe5 fxe5 32. Qd7+ Qxd7 33. Rxd7+
Kg8 34. Kf3 $5 $18) 30. Rxd8 $6 {The second moment when White fails to play in
accordance with the pattern explained above.} (30. Rf2 $1 {White has excellent
chances for a decisive attack.} Nxe5 $6 (30... h6 31. h4 {does not change much.
}) 31. Nxe5 Qxe5 32. Rxf7+ $1 {White might have overlooked this possibility.}
Kxf7 33. Ng5+ Kf6 34. Nxh7+ {winning the queen.}) 30... Qxd8 31. g5 Ne7 32. Nf6
Nf5 33. Qd2 Qxd2+ 34. Nxd2 {Even in the endgame, Black's position remains
difficult.} Nc7 35. Nde4 h6 36. gxh6+ Kxh6 37. Nd7 b5 38. cxb5 (38. Nd6 $5 Kg7
(38... Nxd6 39. exd6 Ne8 40. c5) (38... bxc4 39. bxc4 Kg7 40. Kf3 Nd4+ 41. Ke3
Nc6) 39. Nxf5+ (39. Kf3) 39... exf5 40. c5 Ne6 41. c6 {In these lines, WHite
is very active, but the open question remains whether he can break the
fortress.}) 38... axb5 (38... Nxb5 {finally activates the knight but runs into}
39. Nb8 a5 40. Nc6 {wins the a-pawn.}) 39. a4 Nd4 40. Nd6 b4 41. Nc5 Kg5 (41...
Kg7 $1 {offers better chances for survival.}) 42. Nxf7+ Kf5 43. a5 Nc6 44. a6
g5 45. Kg3 Kg6 46. Nd6 Kh5 47. Nc8 Kg6 48. a7 Kf5 49. Nd7 Kg6 50. Ndb6 Nxe5 51.
Nd6 Nc6 52. Nb5 Nxa7 53. Nxc7 Kf5 54. Nc4 Nc6 55. Na6 Nd4 56. Nc5 Ne2+ 57. Kf2
Nd4 58. Kg2 Kf4 59. Kf2 Kf5 60. Nd2 Nc6 61. Nd3 Kg4 62. Kg2 e5 63. Ne4 1-0

