{Since the Hedgehog is one of my favourite openings with Black, I face certain
psychological problems when playing against it with white. I usually try to
treat it as violently as I can.} 1. g3 c5 2. c4 Nf6 3. Bg2 e6 {I knew that
Constantin also plays the Hedgehog a lot and my move order prevented him to do
it in the proper way.} 4. Nf3 a6 5. Nc3 b6 $6 {He could not resist the
temptation to switch to a Hedgehog under wrse circumstances.} 6. d4 cxd4 7.
Nxd4 Ra7 8. O-O Bb7 9. e4 d6 10. Be3 Nbd7 11. f4 {White has managed to play
e2-e4 without spending a tempo on Re1 or Qc2 and the rook is badly placed on
a7.} Qa8 {Trying to give mean9ing to Black's previous play. Due to the
bishop's presence on e3, White seems to have problems with thfending e4
properly. However, Black's delay in development induces the thought that White
can start attacking.} 12. f5 e5 13. Ne6 $3 {The most principled continuation.}
(13. Nc2 $5 Nxe4 14. Nd5 Bxd5 15. cxd5 Nef6 16. Nb4 {also offers White ample
compensation for the pawn.}) 13... fxe6 14. fxe6 Nc5 (14... Nb8 $2 15. Rxf6
gxf6 16. Qh5+ Kd8 17. Bxb6+ $18 {Now is a first moment when the bishop shows
his teeth.}) 15. Rxf6 $1 {Inspired by Lasker-Pirc.} gxf6 {White is a rook down,
but he has the initiative and great play on the light squares. Soon he will
retrieve part of the material.} 16. Qh5+ Kd8 17. b4 ({I considered} 17. Qf7 $6
{inaccurate, but it seems that I was wrong.} Be7 18. b4 Rf8 (18... Bc6 19. bxc5
bxc5 20. Qg7 Re8 21. Qxh7 {The h-pawn is likely to decide.}) 19. Qh5 $1 {
Preventing the king's retreat to e8.} ({My old analysis went} 19. Qxh7 Nxe6 $13
20. Bxb6+ Ke8 $1) 19... Nxe6 20. Bxb6+ Kd7 21. Bh3 {The pin is decisive.} Bxe4
22. Nxe4 Qxe4 23. Bf5 Qxc4 24. Bxa7 $18) 17... Bc6 (17... Nxe6 18. Qf7 $18) 18.
bxc5 bxc5 {Even though the pawns are equal and White is an exchange down, he
has a bog advantage due to his better coordination and space advantage.} 19.
Rd1 {I could have delayed the rook's development, as I could adjust my plans
according to Black's reactions.} (19. Nd5 $5 Be7 {A neutral move, aiming at
maintaining some flexibility.} (19... Rb7 20. Rf1 Be7 21. Qf7 Bxd5 22. exd5 h5
23. Qg7 Re8 24. Qh7 $18) (19... Qb7 20. Qd1 {followed by Rb1.}) 20. Bd2 $5)
19... Kc8 20. Bh3 (20. Nd5 $16) 20... Be7 21. Qf7 {My play in this phase was
too straightforward. I should have kept the queen available for play on the
opposite wing, where the black king is living. AT this stage, I should have
consolidated the e4-pawn somehow and retreated with the queen to e2.} (21. Bf5)
(21. Nd5) 21... Rc7 22. Bf5 Kb7 23. Bh6 Ka7 {The king has managed to escape
from the centre, but Black's position is not rosy yet.} 24. Bg7 $2 {This was
not a blunder, it was an intended queen sacrifice. I simply seem to have lost
the sense for reality.} ({It was not too late for returning to the right path:
} 24. Qh5 $1 Rb7 25. Qe2 Bf8 26. Bc1 h5 27. h4 $16 {Black remains very passive
and the game is one-sided.}) 24... Be8 25. Nd5 Bxf7 26. Nxc7 Qg8 $1 {This was
the move I missed, but the engines fail to see my compensation for the queen
after other moves, too.} 27. Bxh8 Bh5 28. Bxf6 Bxf6 29. Rxd6 Qg5 30. Nd5 Qc1+
31. Kg2 Qd2+ 32. Kh3 Bf3 33. Rd7+ Kb8 0-1

