{[%evp 0,61,19,29,23,-4,1,-34,-19,-19,19,-34,-21,-22,10,1,13,5,20,34,32,37,-4,
-8,49,-2,36,-8,-14,-16,4,0,-6,10,134,103,102,102,103,137,137,145,118,117,173,
135,122,114,121,144,231,254,258,282,294,285,306,307,307,303,380,330,458,458]
Richard Reti was the pioneer of the opening that bears his name today. Even
though we take it granted nowadays, it was a revolutionary approach to opening
with white pieces at the time. The hypermodernist idea of letting the opponent
push his central pawns, then blocking their further advance and finally
attacking them with pieces was displayed beautifully in a number of Reti's
games in this opening. The double fianchetto was a particulary effective part
of this strategy. For the start, let us take a look at some of the most
important examples of such play from Reti's games and compare them to
contemporary grandmaster practice. 1. Double fianchetto against d5-e5 pawn
center.} 1. Nf3 d5 (1... Nf6 {A modern example to be compared to Reti-Yates:}
2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bg4 5. b3 Nbd7 6. Bb2 e6 7. d3 Be7 8. Nbd2 O-O 9. c4
a5 10. a3 Re8 11. Rc1 h6 12. Rc2 $5 {Zherebukh uses Reti's trademark rook/
queen maneuver:} Bd6 13. Qa1 e5 14. cxd5 cxd5 15. Rfc1 {[#] The position is
quite similar to Reti-Yates (with the exception of Bg4 vs Bc6). What should
black do now?} e4 $6 {is a bad idea as it opens the diagonal for Bb2.} (15...
Qe7 $15 {keeping tension, was one good option and if} 16. e4 {then} d4 {
[%csl Bb2,Bg2] locks up both bishops}) (15... d4 16. Nc4 Bf8 $15 {[%csl Bg2]
was also good, keeping a nice space advantage.}) 16. dxe4 dxe4 {[%csl Ba1,Bb2]}
17. Nd4 Bf8 $2 {Too passive.} ({The only way to justify the previous move was
to sacrifice a pawn with} 17... e3 18. fxe3 Qe7 $44) 18. h3 Bh5 19. Nf1 $1 {
[%csl Be3] Zherebukh now emplys Reti's trademark knight maneuver. The knight
will stand well on e3.} Bg6 20. Ne3 Qb6 21. Nc4 Qa6 22. Ne3 Red8 23. a4 b6 24.
Nb5 $16 {and White had a clear positional advantage thanks to more active
pieces in 1-0 (62) Zherebukh,Y (2677) -Le,T (2902) Chess. com INT 2019 EXT
2021 [dkulj]}) 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bd6 5. b3 O-O 6. O-O Re8 7. Bb2 Nbd7
8. d3 {[%csl Bb2,Bg2] White would like to keep diagonals for both his bishops
open, which is why he plays so modestly with his d-pawn.} (8. d4 {taking space
in the center, is a more classical approach.}) 8... c6 9. Nbd2 e5 10. cxd5 cxd5
{While it looks strong and promising, black pawn center needs constant
attention. White's idea is to attack it with his pieces. Reti's next trademark
maneuver is well-known these days:} 11. Rc1 Nf8 {[#]} 12. Rc2 $5 {A nice way
to mobilize heavy pieces in a position with limited space available.} Bd7 13.
Qa1 {[%csl Bd5,Be5]} Ng6 14. Rfc1 Bc6 {Black overprotects his pawn center and
closes the c-file. His play has been logical and strong so far.} 15. Nf1 $5 {
Another trademark Reti maneuver - the knight is headed to e3 square, from
which it can exert additional pressure on black pawn center.} Qd7 16. Ne3 h6 $2
{A pointless move which will be punished swiftly.} ({Black has put his pieces
on the best squares, so it was the right time to change the pawn structure with
} 16... d4 17. Nc4 Bc7 18. a4 {[%csl Bc4] White has obtained a good outpost
for his knight. However, Black has increased his space advantage and blocked
Bb2-Qa1 battery. It is also important to note that such a passive approach in
the center makes White vulnerable on the flanks. Thus, the most principled
continuation is} h5 $1 $40 {exploiting the fact that white pieces are stuck on
the queenside.} (18... Nd5 $5 $15 {also makes sense})) 17. d4 $1 {A perfect
timing for the attack on black center.} e4 18. Ne5 Bxe5 19. dxe5 Nh7 20. f4 $5
{Reti tries to increase his central control with this move.} (20. Rd2 $16 {
was also possible}) 20... exf3 21. exf3 Ng5 $2 {Black is not fighting for
central control with this move and his position soon becomes very bad.} ({
Black should have undermined white pawn center with} 21... f6 {although after}
22. f4 fxe5 23. f5 $1 (23. fxe5 Ng5 $132) 23... Ne7 24. Bxe5 $14 {White is
still in control of the position thanks to his better centralization.}) 22. f4
Nh3+ (22... Ne4 {fails to} 23. Rd1 Qe6 24. f5 $18) 23. Kh1 {[%csl Rb2,Re3,Rg2]
An ideal piece placement in the double fianchetto - both bishops are powerful
and other pieces work in harmony. Black is out of good ideas in a
strategically losing position and he goes for broke with} d4 24. Bxd4 Rad8 {
but to no avail:} 25. Rxc6 $1 bxc6 26. Bxc6 Nf2+ 27. Kg2 Qxd4 28. Qxd4 Rxd4 29.
Bxe8 Ne4 30. e6 Rd2+ 31. Kf3 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

