{[%evp 0,61,19,18,19,-4,0,0,33,20,30,22,17,5,25,-1,6,6,6,8,22,23,13,3,36,-11,
47,10,19,19,19,19,24,16,14,-3,2,1,7,7,7,-63,-70,-66,-78,-77,-50,-33,-32,-24,
-19,-25,-27,-28,-16,-29,-21,-20,-21,-21,-18,-15,-17,-21] 2. Double fianchetto
against the Queen's Indian/hanging pawns structure.} 1. Nf3 ({A modern example:
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 Bb4+ 5. Nd2 O-O 6. Ngf3 b6 7. O-O Bb7 8.
b3 $5 {A double fianchetto approach has recently gained many followers, even
among top GMs, in this popular Catalan position. It may not seem too ambitious
at first, but it is quite flexible. White is hoping to force a hanging pawns
structure since his fianchettoed bishops are quite effective against it.} ({
Other popular lines are} 8. Ne5) ({and} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. a3) 8... Nbd7 9. Bb2
Qe7 10. Ne5 $146 Rfd8 11. Nd3 Bd6 12. e3 {This move is mainly aimed fat making
the e2-spot vacant for the queen.} Rab8 {Protecting the bishop wasn't a
necessary measure.} (12... c5 $5 {was quite possible:} 13. cxd5 exd5 14. dxc5
bxc5 15. Rc1 Rac8 $132) 13. Rc1 Ne4 14. cxd5 {It makes sense to clarify the
pawn structure - the pressure on the Pd5 is starting to tell.} exd5 15. Re1 $1
{An excellent prophylactic move - there is no reason to touch the Nd2 for a
while.} c5 (15... f5 16. Nf3 c6 17. Nfe5 $14) 16. dxc5 bxc5 17. Qc2 $14 {
[%csl Gb2,Gg2] Double fianchetto is usually quite effective against the
hanging pawns since the bishops control many important squares in the center
and can attack the pawns.} Rbc8 18. Nf4 {[%csl Bd5] An important outpost for
the knight in this structure, increasing pressure against the hanging pawns.}
Nef6 $2 {[#] As a result, Black doesn't withstand the pressure. Hou Yifan is
unlocking the long diagonal and inviting fresh troubles.} ({In the case of} 
18... Ndf6 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. Rcd1 Bc7 {[#] White can destroy the pawn center
with a thematic exhange sacrifice:} 21. Nxd5 $1 Bxd5 22. Rxd5 Rxd5 23. Bxe4 Rh5
24. Bf3 Rh6 25. Qc3 $16) 19. Nc4 $1 {This is the thematic knight move from
Reti-Marshall that should be remembered in such positions.} (19. Nb1 c4) 19...
Bc7 20. Red1 {Now the pressure on the hanging pawns is so big, that Black has
to exchange the powerful dark-squared bishop.} Bxf4 (20... Nb6 21. Na5) (20...
Nf8 21. Bxf6) 21. exf4 $1 {Opening-up the e-file causes Black even more
problems.} Ba8 22. Ne3 $16 {[%csl Be3,Bg2,Bb2] White achieved an ideal
position of his pieces in 0-1 (34) Meier,G (2621)-Hou,Y (2649) Karlsruhe/
Baden-Baden 2017 CBM 178 [Roiz,M]. The following sample line shows how his
positional domination can be transformed into something more tangible:} d4 23.
Nf5 Qf8 24. Bxd4 Bxg2 25. Kxg2 cxd4 26. Qxc8 Rxc8 27. Rxc8 $18) 1... d5 2. g3
Nf6 3. Bg2 Nbd7 4. d4 e6 5. O-O Bd6 6. c4 O-O 7. Nbd2 b6 8. b3 Bb7 9. Bb2 Rc8
10. Ne5 Qe7 11. Rc1 c5 {[%csl Bg2,Bb2,Bc5,Bd5] Such positions with central
tension are very popular these days, usually arising from the Catalan or Reti
openings.} 12. Nxd7 Nxd7 {[#] This is the critical position in the early
middlegame. White has a couple of options, which one is the best?} 13. e4 $6 {
Reti's choice is not so great.} ({The right idea was:} 13. cxd5 exd5 (13...
Bxd5 14. e4 Ba8 15. Nc4 Bb8 16. d5 $16) 14. Nc4 $1 {A thematic knight maneuver
worth remembering (an alternative version from Reti-Yates). White either wins
the bishop pair or transfers his knight to the perfect e3 square.} dxc4 (14...
Rfd8 15. Ne3 $16 {d5-pawn cannot be defended in the long run - mission
accomplished for White.}) (14... Bb8 15. Ne3 $18) 15. Bxb7 Rc7 16. Bd5 cxb3 17.
Bxb3 $16 {White won the bishop pair, which promises a significant advantage
once the center fully opens up.}) (13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. Bxd5 exd5
$14 {is still quite solid for Black}) 13... dxe4 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Bxe4 Nf6 16.
Bb1 $6 {A wrong choice of diagonal, the bishop will not be effective there.} (
16. Bf3 {was better, though black is still quite solid after} cxd4 17. Qxd4
Rfd8) 16... cxd4 17. Bxd4 Bc5 18. Be5 Rcd8 19. Qc2 g6 $1 {The move that shuts
down Bb1.} 20. Qc3 Ng4 21. Bg7 Rfe8 22. h3 f6 $1 23. hxg4 Kxg7 $10 24. Rcd1
Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Rd8 26. Rxd8 Qxd8 27. Qd3 Qxd3 28. Bxd3 f5 29. gxf5 exf5 30. Kg2
Kf6 31. f4 {1/2-1/2 The game is a draw.} 1/2-1/2

