29,40,40,26,29,89,60,90,92,79,45,87,92,112,103,137,178,227,199,176,216,255,256,
241,206,207,115,112,154,153,218,187,198,203,210,212,222,233,223,290,285,287,
319,307,265,315,292,292,337,371,395] 3. Extended double fianchetto/reversed
Benko gambit} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 g6 4. c4 d4 5. d3 Bg7 6. b4 $1 {
[%csl Bd4] Extended fianchetto - these days it is a normal idea and a
theoretical move in this position, but Reti was one of the first players to
use it successfully on the highest level, as we can see in his win against
Rubinstein below.} O-O 7. Nbd2 $5 {preparing to attack the isolated d4 pawn
with Nb3.} ({A modern example:} 7. O-O c5 8. Nbd2 (8. bxc5 Nfd7 9. Ba3 Qc7 10.
Nbd2 Nxc5 11. Nb3 Ne6 $13) 8... cxb4 9. Nb3 Nc6 10. a3 bxa3 11. Bxa3 $44 {
We have a reversed Benko-gambit. White has a lead in development and puts
pressure on black position with his bishop pair.} Re8 12. Qc2 Bg4 13. h3 Bxf3
14. Bxf3 {[%csl Bf3,Ba3] White has full compensation for the pawn} Qc7 (14...
Rc8 15. Rfb1 b6 16. Nd2 Qd7 $13) 15. Rfb1 Nd7 16. Nd2 Rac8 17. Qa4 b6 18. Nb3
e5 19. c5 $36 {1/2-1/2 (75) Khismatullin,D (2654)-Li,C (2750) Doha 2015}) (7.
Bb2 c5 8. bxc5 Nc6) 7... c5 $6 {Not the most accurate way to give support to
d4-pawn.} (7... a5 8. b5 c5 $13) (7... Re8 8. Nb3 e5 $13 {[%csl Yd4] are both
better options.}) 8. Nb3 $1 {The most principled move - making sure that
d4-pawn is destroyed.} (8. bxc5 Nfd7 9. Nb3 (9. Ba3 Qa5) 9... Nxc5 10. Nxc5
Qa5+ 11. Qd2 Qxc5 12. Rb1 $14) (8. Bb2 $6 Nc6 9. bxc5 Nd7 10. Nb3 Nxc5) 8...
cxb4 9. Bb2 Nc6 10. Nbxd4 Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {Black pawn center has vanished -
mission completed.} b6 12. a3 Bb7 13. Bb2 bxa3 14. Rxa3 Qc7 15. Qa1 $14 {
Reti carries out a version of his trademark rook-queen maneuver. His pieces
are placed perfectly.} Ne8 16. Bxg7 Nxg7 17. O-O Ne6 18. Rb1 Bc6 19. d4 $1 {
White finally puts his pawn center in motion.} Be4 20. Rd1 a5 21. d5 $1 {
Reti gives away an outpost on c5, but obtains control of a more important one
- on c6.} Nc5 22. Nd4 Bxg2 23. Kxg2 Rfd8 24. Nc6 $16 {This is an important
positional motif in Reti's games} Rd6 25. Re3 Re8 {Too passive.} ({Black
should have eliminated the powerful knight while he had a chance.} 25... Rxc6
$5 26. dxc6 Qxc6+ $16) 26. Qe5 f6 27. Qb2 e5 28. Qb5 Kf7 29. Rb1 Nd7 30. f3 Rc8
31. Rd3 e4 32. fxe4 Ne5 33. Qxb6 Nxc6 34. c5 Rd7 35. dxc6 Rxd3 36. Qxc7+ Rxc7
37. exd3 Rxc6 38. Rb7+ Ke8 39. d4 $18 Ra6 40. Rb6 Ra8 41. Rxf6 a4 42. Rf2 a3
43. Ra2 Kd7 44. d5 g5 45. Kf3 Ra4 46. Ke3 h5 47. h4 gxh4 48. gxh4 Ke7 49. Kf4
Kd7 50. Kf5 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

