{[%evp 0,61,29,15,39,-3,38,-18,-9,-47,-20,-48,24,8,-6,-10,4,4,4,-4,-1,-24,-18,
-15,-13,-19,-18,-36,-4,-5,11,10,16,-7,-13,-24,-24,-45,3,-5,0,-6,-15,-15,-15,6,
34,-8,11,32,65,65,83,93,73,98,97,152,135,136,175,151,231,218] 4. Double
fianchetto against double fianchetto. This was Reti's greatest victory -
against the (at that moment) unbeaten World Champion!} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 g6 3.
b4 $5 {Reti uses extended fianchetto, as we have seen in game 3.} Bg7 4. Bb2
O-O 5. g3 b6 6. Bg2 Bb7 {Capablanca answers with a double fianchetto himself!}
7. O-O d6 ({A modern example from a game of Vladimir Kramnik.} 7... d5 $6 {
is not a good move here since after} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 9. Bxg7 Kxg7 {the exchange
of dark-squared bishops weakens black position (as in Reti-Capablanca)} 10. Qb3
Nd7 11. Nc3 Nxc3 12. Qxc3+ Kg8 13. d4 Nf6 14. Rfd1 $16 {[%csl Bc7] The b4-pawn
is important as it keeps c5-break in check.} Rc8 {[#]} 15. Ne5 $1 {Following
Reti's strategy to plant the knight on c6.} (15. d5 $6 {is tempting but runs
into} c6 $1 16. dxc6 Rxc6 $11) 15... Bxg2 16. Kxg2 {[%csl Bc6]} Qd6 (16... Qd5+
17. f3 c5 18. e4 $18) 17. a3 Qe6 18. Qc6 Qf5 19. Rac1 Rfd8 20. Qf3 Qxf3+ 21.
Kxf3 a6 22. Nc6 {The knight is firmly placed on the c6-outpost and White is
strategically winning.} Rd7 23. d5 Kf8 24. e4 $18 {1-0 (57) Kramnik,V (2753)
-Tsydypov,Z (2558) Lichess.org INT 2020}) 8. d3 Nbd7 9. Nbd2 e5 10. Qc2 Re8 11.
Rfd1 a5 12. a3 h6 {Black should be more or less happy with the opening outcome
- his position is not worse. Of course, the full battle is still ahead and
this is one of the advantages of double fianchetto in the modern computer era
- since the central structure is still very fluid and all pieces are on the
board, Black can hardly simplify matters to force a draw out of the opening  
(which is often the case in some classical openings).} 13. Nf1 c5 $2 {A
tactical oversight...} (13... e4 $5 $11) 14. b5 $2 {...which is mutual.} ({
Both players missed the tactic} 14. Nxe5 $1 Bxg2 15. Nxd7 $16 {when White wins
a full pawn. Psychologically, one hardly expects for a tactic to exist in such
a quiet position, which might explain the mutual oversight.}) 14... Nf8 15. e3
Qc7 16. d4 $2 {This opening of the center is premature.} ({It would have
probably been better to try to explaoint the newly created weakness on d5 with
} 16. N1d2 Ne6 17. Ne4 $5 Nxe4 18. dxe4 $14) 16... Be4 17. Qc3 exd4 18. exd4
N6d7 $2 {Too passive. Capablanca falters in the critical moment in the
middlegame.} ({Instead, after} 18... Ne6 $1 {[%csl Bd4] White would not be
able to keep his pawn center. After} 19. dxc5 dxc5 $17 {black pieces are
placed better.}) 19. Qd2 {Now d6 is a weakness. Capablanca makes things worse
with the following central exchange.} cxd4 $6 20. Bxd4 Qxc4 21. Bxg7 Kxg7 22.
Qb2+ $1 Kg8 23. Rxd6 $16 {Black has a weak b6-pawn, weaknesses on the dark
squares and...} Qc5 24. Rad1 Ra7 25. Ne3 Qh5 26. Nd4 $1 {...a weak c6-square!}
Bxg2 27. Kxg2 Qe5 28. Nc4 Qc5 29. Nc6 $18 {Where have we seen this before? :)
Black position is strategically losing even though he has not lost any
material yet.} Rc7 30. Ne3 Ne5 31. R1d5 {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

