{[%evp 0,81,17,-3,-3,-22,13,15,15,-45,-37,-25,-21,-13,-19,-6,-2,-9,6,6,12,-6,0,
-9,23,2,23,-15,6,-17,46,2,53,41,42,51,51,13,46,18,0,21,21,-16,-13,-15,16,13,63,
60,84,32,-7,0,19,28,50,41,52,52,73,13,17,33,37,35,30,51,22,32,49,35,45,80,54,
56,54,77,231,247,226,223,191,191] 5. Double fianchetto against the solid Slav
setup - a classical example.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 c6 3. Nf3 d5 4. b3 Bf5 5. Bg2 e6
6. Bb2 Nbd7 7. O-O h6 8. d3 Be7 9. Nbd2 O-O 10. a3 a5 11. Qc2 {This move is a
start of the most popular plan for White in this position: /\Bc3,Qb2,b4} (11.
Rc1 {followed by Rc2, Qa1, etc. is Reti's plan}) (11. Qb1 $5 {was played by
Richard Rapport in the next game.}) 11... Bh7 (11... Qb6 $6 12. Bc3 $14) 12.
Bc3 b5 $5 {A rather popular way to deal with White's plan of queenside
expansion. However, it can be structurally risky since it leaves some
potential weaknesses behind (c6, c5)} ({Alternatively, Black could also
prepare ...e5 with} 12... Qb8 $5 13. Qb2 Bd6 14. b4 e5 $132 {and we have the
d5-e5 central pawn structure that was discussed in the first example.}) 13.
cxb5 cxb5 14. b4 Qc7 {/\Rfc8} 15. Qb2 (15. bxa5 b4 16. axb4 Rfc8 17. Rfc1 Bxb4
$11) 15... Nb6 16. Be5 Qd7 17. Nb3 $1 {Botvinnik increases his control over
the dark square complex thanks to a small tactic.} axb4 18. axb4 Rxa1 (18...
Bxb4 $2 {does not work due to} 19. Qd4) 19. Rxa1 Na4 20. Qd2 (20. Qd4 $2 Ne8 {
/\f6}) 20... Rc8 {The position is quite rich, despite the fairly symmetrical
pawn structure. White has a number of reasonable plans at his disposal.} 21.
Rc1 (21. Bh3 $5 {in order to activate the bishop and prevent ...Nfd7, ...f6...
e5 plan, looks like a good alternative, for example:} Qb7 {/\Nd7><b4} 22. Nbd4
Nd7 {[#]} 23. Nxe6 $1 fxe6 24. Bxe6+ Kh8 25. Bd4 $40) (21. h3 {[%csl Bf6][%cal
Bf6d7,Bd7b8,Bb8c6,Bg3g4]} Qb7 {[%csl Bf6,Bd7][%cal Be6d7]} 22. g4 Nd7) (21. Bd4
{[%cal Gf3e5]}) (21. Na5 {leaves the knight a bit misplaced on a5 - it would
be placed better on c5 or d4.}) (21. Nfd4 $5) 21... Rxc1+ 22. Nxc1 Ne8 (22...
Qc8 $1 $132 {/\Nd7-b8-a6><b4 Botvinnik} 23. Nb3 Nd7 24. Ba1 Nb8 25. Nbd4 Na6)
23. Nd4 $1 {a nice move, preventing 23...f6} Kf8 $1 {A strong regrouping by
Smyslov - preparing to improve his passive Bh7.} (23... f6 {is met by} 24. Bh3
$1) 24. Bh3 $1 Bg8 {/\f6} 25. Ndb3 f6 26. Ba1 $1 {/\d4,Nc5} Qa7 27. d4 $13 Nd6
(27... Nb6 $5 {was better, in order to improve the knight on the rim. The
position would remain approximately balanced.}) 28. Qa2 Nc4 29. Nc5 {[%csl Ba4]
Na4 is a problem for Black now, especially after the following exchange:} Bxc5
30. dxc5 {[%csl Ra4] It is almost completely isolated now. Botvinnik will
demonstrate the right strategy of playing with an extra piece on the other
side of the board in the remainder of the game.} e5 (30... Qf7 $1 31. Qc2 Qh5
$10 {Botvinnik}) 31. Qb1 $36 d4 32. Qf5 Qc7 (32... Nxc5 $2 33. Qc8+ Kf7 34.
bxc5 Qxa1 35. Be6+ Kg6 36. Qe8+ $18) 33. Nd3 Bf7 34. Qh7 Bg8 35. Qe4 $1 Bf7 36.
Qa8+ Be8 37. Bg2 $16 Ke7 38. f4 $1 {[#] A timely moment to attack black center
and put the bishops to work.} Ne3 (38... Nc3 $1 39. fxe5 (39. Bxc3 dxc3 40. Qa1
c2 41. Qc1 Bc6 $1 $10) 39... fxe5 40. c6 $1 {Prins} Nxe2+ 41. Kf2 Nc3 42. Qb7
Kd6 43. Bxc3 dxc3 44. Nc5 Bxc6 45. Bxc6 Qxc6 46. Ne4+ Kd5 47. Nxc3+ Kd6 48.
Nxb5+ Kd5 49. Qf7+ $1 $18) 39. fxe5 fxe5 40. Qe4 Nxg2 41. Nxe5 $1 $18 {1-0
Black resigned in the view of} Ne3 42. Bxd4 Nd1 43. Ng6+ Kd8 44. Be5 $18 1-0

