{[%evp 0,65,5,7,21,-18,-14,-16,-16,-38,-7,-7,-6,-45,4,-7,12,-1,9,1,15,-1,2,-24,
7,11,3,-4,-7,6,37,23,17,22,8,8,8,9,35,25,47,42,57,-29,-9,0,165,-14,56,75,75,
129,147,131,240,165,128,148,148,151,177,260,267,286,287,286,292,298] 5. Double
fianchetto against the solid Slav setup - a modern example.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. b3
Bf5 3. Bb2 e6 4. d3 h6 5. Nbd2 Nf6 6. c4 c6 7. g3 {Richard Reti's namesake
plays the same opening almost 100 years later!} Be7 8. Bg2 O-O 9. O-O Nbd7 ({
Black has a different plan at his disposal:} 9... Bh7 10. a3 a5 11. Qc2 Na6 $5
{working hard to prevent White's b3-b4 break.} 12. Bc3 c5 {[%csl Bb4] Black
has managed to prevent b3-b4 and gained some space advantage in the center.
What should White do?} 13. Rad1 ({Instead, it would have been better to strike
at the center at once with} 13. cxd5 exd5 14. e4 $1 $13 {with a complex
middlegame ahead.} d4 (14... dxe4 15. dxe4 {[%csl Ra6][%cal Gf3e5]}) 15. Bb2 {
[%csl Ge4,Gf2][%cal Gf2f4,Gd2c4]}) 13... d4 14. Bb2 Nd7 15. e3 e5 {Black has a
space advantage now and White does not have that much to show for it.} 16. Rfe1
Re8 17. exd4 exd4 18. h3 Qc7 19. Bc1 {[%csl Bc1] improves the inactive bishop}
Nf6 20. Nh2 {[%csl Bg2]} Qd7 21. Ndf1 Nb8 $1 {Black does the same with his
knight} 22. g4 $5 Nc6 23. f4 Bd6 24. f5 {[%csl Rg1,Rg3] Shuts down the bishop
on h7, but leaves some weaknesses behind} Qc7 25. Qf2 a4 $1 $132 {Aronian
obtains timely counterplay on the queenside.} 26. bxa4 Rxa4 27. h4 Rxe1 28.
Rxe1 Ne5 29. Qe2 Nfd7 30. Be4 Nf6 31. Bg2 Nfd7 32. Be4 Nf6 33. Bg2 Nfd7 34. Bh3
b5 $1 35. cxb5 c4 36. g5 Nxd3 37. Qc2 Bxh2+ 38. Kh1 Ra8 39. Rd1 Bf4 40. Rxd3
cxd3 41. Qxc7 Bxc7 42. g6 Bd6 43. gxh7+ Kxh7 44. Bg2 Rc8 45. Bd2 Bxa3 46. f6
Bc1 47. Bh3 Bxd2 48. Bxd7 Rc1 49. Kg2 g6 50. b6 Bf4 51. Bb5 d2 {0-1 (51)
Maghsoodloo,P (2688)-Aronian,L (2765) St Petersburg 2018}) 10. a3 a5 {Stopping
White from expanding on the queenside with b4.} 11. Qb1 $5 {Preparing b4
anyway, using a little tactic.} Bh7 12. b4 axb4 13. axb4 Qb6 (13... Bxb4 $2 14.
Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Rxa8 Rxa8 16. Qxb4 $18) 14. Bc3 Rxa1 15. Qxa1 Bxb4 16. Bxb4 Qxb4
17. Rb1 Qd6 18. Rxb7 e5 19. d4 $1 {Reti's central pawn break from the game
against Yates.} exd4 (19... e4 20. Ne5 {gives White a central outpost.}) 20.
Nxd4 c5 21. N4b3 $1 {[%csl Bc5] A nice move - setting sights on c5-pawn and
keeping White's piece coordination} (21. Nb5 {was more active, but Black can
get counterplay with} Qe6 22. cxd5 Qxe2) 21... d4 $5 {An ambitious move. If
Magnus wanted a quieter, simplified game, he could've opted for 21...dxc4. But
probably Magnus, after a heartbreaking draw last round against Anish Giri,
wanted to try hard to win this game with Black against Richard Rapport, who
had been having a difficult tournament up to this point.} (21... dxc4 22. Nxc4
Qe6 23. Ne3 Be4 24. Bxe4 Nxe4 {should just be dead equal.}) 22. Bh3 d3 $6 {
This decision is very double-edged since it makes Black's bishop on h7 bad,
and gives White strong control of the centre. On the other hand, Magnus thinks
that the d3-pawn will be enough of a trump, that it will compensate for the
drawbacks in his position. It turned out to be a bit too optimistic.} (22...
Rb8 23. Rxb8+ Qxb8 24. Qa5 Qc8 {should still be quite balanced.}) 23. e3 $1 {
[#] White correctly now doesn't simplify the game, and keeps the tension to
his advantage. A lot of players might have just tried to release the tension
to get closer to a draw if they were playing Magnus. But Richard to his credit
is a very fighting player, even when his tournament isn't going the way he
would like it to be. I really applaud that.} (23. exd3 $6 Qxd3) (23. e4 $5)
23... Ne5 $6 {A natural move, but considering that Black had already started
playing unbalanced chess he should probably have tried to continue going that
route.} (23... g5 $1 {After this prophylactic move White might be better but
it's still not so clear. At least White can't easily expand in the centre,
like he was able to do in the game.} 24. Qa5 (24. Qa4 Rd8 25. Bg2 g4 {[%csl
Bf2,Bf4][%cal Bf2f4]}) (24. Bg2 Bg6) 24... g4 25. Bg2 Rc8) (23... Rb8 24. Rxb8+
Qxb8 25. Qa4) 24. Bg2 $1 (24. f4 $2 Nf3+ $1 25. Nxf3 Be4 $15 {was a nice trap
by Magnus, and perhaps Richard saw it and that's why avoided it and played the
strong consolidating move, Bg2.}) 24... Rc8 (24... Ned7 {The funny thing is,
Stockfish thinks going back with Ned7 is the best move. The knight on e5 turns
out to be really misplaced, since it will get hit with e4 and f4.}) (24... Re8
25. Qa7) 25. f4 Neg4 26. e4 Re8 $5 {At this point sacrifising a piece might be
the best practical chance, since Black is already getting streamrollered.} 27.
e5 Nxe5 28. fxe5 Rxe5 29. Rb6 $1 {Very nice geometry.} Qe7 30. Rb8+ Ne8 31. Bc6
Re1+ 32. Qxe1 Qxe1+ 33. Nf1 {Black resigned because he will be down a piece in
the endgame which is completely hopeless. A very nice game by Richard Rapport,
trying to play a fighting game against Magnus, playing logical chess, keeping
the tension, and taking full advantage of Magnus's over-ambitious play at one
moment.} 1-0

