{[%evp 0,71,41,16,25,-2,-10,-15,10,6,14,-2,-3,-2,-7,13,23,13,10,5,17,25,18,23,
33,13,0,0,9,9,9,79,72,72,42,39,39,27,27,44,49,61,65,30,43,58,58,25,40,67,47,70,
70,77,60,67,123,70,64,62,128,128,121,135,128,125,120,128,116,124,372,385,400,
402] 5. Double fianchetto against the solid Slav setup - my own example.} 1.
Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 c6 4. O-O Bf5 5. c4 {The Reti opening is quite a good
option if you know that your opponent plays 1...d5 and you just want to get a
reasonable game without much opening theory.} (5. b3 {is a more typical way to
get into a double fianchetto type of position here.}) 5... e6 6. cxd5 exd5 7.
d3 Be7 8. Nc3 O-O 9. Qc2 {[%cal Be2e4]} d4 {A principled move that prevents 10.
e4.} 10. Ne4 $5 {Other knight moves were possible, too, but this continuation
seemed to offer more complicated play. I was trying to exploit my opponent's
lack of experience with non-standard pawn structures. Black already has an
important strategic decision to make with regard to exchange on e4.} Na6 (10...
Nxe4 {would probably be premature, since White obtains initiative in the
center simply:} 11. dxe4 Be6 12. Rd1 c5 13. b4 b6 14. e3) 11. a3 Re8 {Yang
probably prepared the exchange on e4 with this move.} (11... Rc8 12. b4 c5 {
and Black would be completely fine.}) 12. b4 {The extended double fianchetto.}
Nxe4 {A concrete decision - not unexpected for a young player.} (12... Rc8 {
was probably better anyway, preparing 13...c5.}) 13. dxe4 Bg6 14. Bb2 (14. Ne5
$2 Bf6 15. Nxg6 d3 $1) 14... Bf6 {The e4-pawn is hanging and White has to move
his knight to protect it. The obvious move is 15.Nd2, continuing the
positional fight. However, I came up with an interesting idea to open up the
position by sacrificing a pawn:} 15. Nxd4 $5 (15. Nd2) 15... Bxd4 16. Rad1 {
Now, everything is pretty much forced:} Bxf2+ 17. Rxf2 Qe7 18. Qc3 f6 {[#]} 19.
e5 $1 {This pawn advance, in connection with the following one, was the key
positional idea that I had to find in advance; otherwise I would not have
played 15.Nxd4.} fxe5 20. b5 $1 cxb5 21. Qb3+ Kh8 22. Qxb5 {[%csl Bg2,Bb2,Be5,
Bb7] This is the position I was aiming for. The point, that I thought my young
opponent might not fully appreciate, is that white bishops are very strong not
only in the short, but also in the long run. I could imagine many endgames in
which they would promise White an advantage against the knight and bishop pair.
However, Black's position is also unpleasant in the middlegame since his piece
coordination is not so good and he has several weakneses, such as d7-square,
b7- and e5-pawns. I would probably play the same sequence against anyone, but
I thought that it might be particularly tricky for a less experienced opponent
because Black's defensive task is not straightforward.} Nc7 {Black uses a
tactical detail: Bb2 would be undefended in case of 23.Qxb7 Rab8.} (22... Rab8
{due to a small tactic:} 23. Bxe5 $1 Qxe5 24. Rf8+ Rxf8 25. Qxe5 $18) 23. Qa4 (
23. Qd7 Rab8 24. Qxe7 Rxe7 {and while White has full compensation and probably
some more, I thought that there was no need to simplify my opponent's
defensive task.}) 23... b5 {The first sign of youthful impatience. Although
the move itself is not so bad, it does create some new weaknesses.} (23... a5
24. Rd7 Qc5 25. Qd1 h6 $14) (23... Red8 $5 24. Rxd8+ Rxd8 25. Qxa7 $14 h6 26.
Qxb7 Qc5 $1 $44) 24. Qa5 e4 $2 {[#] This, however, is a serious positional
mistake. While trying to keep material advantage, Black granted white
dark-squared bishop a wide open long diagonal to aim at his king. This is a
huge long-term positional concession, as every Nimzo-Indian player knows. A
player with better-developed positional intuition would not play this move,
but this is easily forgivable in case of a young player because perfecting
positional play takes more time than tactical one.} (24... Rad8 25. Rxd8 Rxd8
26. Qxa7 h6 $14 {where White would keep some pressure due to his bishop pair
advantage.}) 25. Bh3 $1 {[%csl Bb2,Bh3,Bg7,Bd7] White finds new employment for
his bishop. Rd1-d7 is too strong of a threat, so Black has to play:} Rad8 {
after all.} 26. Rxd8 Rxd8 27. Qxa7 $16 {White established material equality
and with the open dark-squared bishop, his positional advantage is quite
serious.} e3 {A natural move, although not without positional risks.} (27... h5
{giving some air to the king, would have been more patient.}) 28. Rf1 Bh5 $5 {
[#] Once again, Black tries to solve his problems in a concrete manner. During
the game, I thought that this was a losing move, but it turns out to be very
decent.} (28... Rd2 $4 {loses to} 29. Qxc7 $18) (28... Nd5 {leads to a very
unpleasant endgame for Black after:} 29. Qxe7 Nxe7 30. Bc3 $16) 29. Rc1 {
This leads by force to an endgame in which I intuitively felt that White
should be winning. However, things are not so simple.} Bxe2 30. Qxc7 Qxc7 (
30... Rd1+ 31. Rxd1 Qxc7 {White has a nice refutation:} 32. Rd7 $1 Qb8 33.
Bxg7+ Kg8 34. Be6#) 31. Rxc7 Rd1+ 32. Kg2 Bf1+ 33. Kf3 Bxh3 34. Rxg7 {[#]
White has achieved a complete domination on the long diagonal. Black king is
indefinitely trapped in the corner and it looks like a discovered check at the
right moment should decide the game. This indeed happened in the game, after a
time-trouble mistake by Yang:} Rd2 $4 (34... Rb1 $1 {black rook would be
shielded from discovered attack by his b-pawn and} 35. Bd4 h6 $16 {would lead
to a pawn-up opposite-colored bishops endgame where White would still have to
work for the full point.}) 35. Bc3 $1 {The key intermediate move. Black rook
will not find a safe haven now.} Rd3 (35... Rc2 36. Be5 Rc5 37. Rg5+ $18 {
is similar.}) 36. Be5 {and Black resigned due to threats Rg5# and Rd7+.} 1-0

