{[%evp 0,71,23,21,27,-10,30,29,26,3,3,3,9,7,25,27,28,28,28,25,27,15,14,-11,40,
42,42,42,46,47,42,20,26,17,49,-4,-3,9,10,8,81,78,57,58,58,58,119,149,329,342,
345,332,340,340,356,327,356,368,415,387,411,333,347,407,414,336,369,437,438,
452,452,522,522,497] 6. Double fianchetto against Gruenfeld defense.} 1. Nf3 d5
({A more typical Gruenfeld move order to reach a similar structure is:} 1...
Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 d5 5. c4 c6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. O-O {etc.}) 2. g3 c6 3.
Bg2 Bg4 4. b3 Nd7 5. Bb2 Ngf6 6. d3 g6 7. Nbd2 Bg7 8. O-O O-O 9. c4 Re8 10. Rc1
e5 {Black builds up the e5-d5 pawn center, but this time White can win the
bishop pair with} 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 $14 {[#] White position
should be slightly more promising. Not only has he won the bishop pair, so
that his ligh-squared bishop has no match; he has also managed to trade a pair
of pieces, which allows him to maneuver his pieces more easily. How should
Black proceed now?} e4 $6 {opening the long diagonal for Bb2 was not such a
good idea.} (13... d4 {is similarly premature due to} 14. Ng5) (13... Qa5 14.
Rc2) (13... Qb6 $5 14. e3 a5 {seems like the most sensible way to keep the
tension while looking for queenside counterplay.}) ({The engine suggests a
slightly artificial maneuver} 13... Bf8 $5 14. e3 Bd6) 14. Nd4 {White also
gets a comfortable outpost for the knight now.} ({Perhaps even more in the
spirit of the hypermodernist idea was:} 14. dxe4 dxe4 15. Nd2 $5 {provoking
Black into opening the center completely with} e3 16. Nc4 $36 {[%csl Bb2,Bc4,
Bg2]} exf2+ 17. Rxf2 {White bishops dominate and the knight sits perfectly on
c4.}) 14... Qb6 (14... e3 15. f4 $1 Nh5 16. Qe1 Qb6 17. g4 Bxd4 18. Bxd4 Qxd4
19. gxh5 $14 {[%csl Bd5]}) 15. Nc2 {An interesting piece regrouping - bishop
goes to d4 and the knight to e3.} Qa6 16. a3 Rad8 17. Nb4 $5 Qb5 18. Bd4 {
[%csl Bd4,Bb4]} Nh5 $6 {As we have seen many times so far, the exhange of
dark-squared bishops is in White's favor.} (18... Bf8 $14 {was better, keeping
the tension.}) 19. Bxg7 Nxg7 $2 {A tactical mistake.} (19... Kxg7 20. dxe4 dxe4
21. Nd5 $36 {is still tricky for Black, but at least f6-square is covered.})
20. dxe4 dxe4 21. Nd5 {Black has serious tactical problems on the dark squares
now.} Qa5 {[#]} 22. b4 $1 {The winning move.} (22. Rc7 $5 Ne5 23. Nf6+ Kh8 24.
Qc1 Re6 25. Nxe4 $18) 22... Qxa3 23. Qc2 $1 $18 {Black queen is trapped and he
loses material.} Nf5 24. Ra1 Nd4 25. Qd2 Nxe2+ 26. Qxe2 Qb3 27. Rfd1 Kg7 28.
Rab1 Qa3 29. Nc7 Re7 30. Nb5 Qa6 31. Rd6 b6 32. Rbd1 Qb7 33. Qb2+ Kg8 34. Nc3
f5 35. Nd5 Rf7 36. Nf6+ {1-0 Black resigns.} 1-0

