{[%evp 0,67,32,-12,14,26,31,3,20,-25,10,-4,19,7,18,7,34,34,30,30,35,7,7,2,16,
20,11,-12,1,-8,-19,-41,-32,-47,-58,-28,-37,-39,-56,-72,-72,-71,-9,-14,-9,-15,
-13,-13,16,0,-33,-33,7,-129,-143,-161,-143,-242,-206,-212,-231,-211,-205,-236,
-215,-213,-219,-219,-161,-172] 7. Double fianchetto against King's Indian
defense with Nge7} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. b3 e5 4. Bb2 d6 5. Nc3 g6 6. g3 Bg7
7. Bg2 Nge7 {[%csl Be7] Generally speaking, these KID positions are slightly
better for Black with the knight on e7 than on f6 because he can push ...f7-f5
more quickly. It should also be noted that Bb2 is not that effective in this
structure - it is blocked by the pawn chain c5-d6-e5. In return, White will
try to take control over the weakened d5-square.} 8. O-O O-O 9. d3 Rb8 10. Ne1
{[%cal Ge1c2,Gc2e3,Ge3d5] White starts the maneuver to take control over
d5-square.} (10. Nd2 $5 {is an alternative.}) 10... Be6 11. Nd5 Qd7 {[%csl Ge6]
[%cal Ge6h3] Black's idea is to exchange light-squared bishops, weakening
white king and reducing his control over d5-square.} ({and} 11... b5 $5) (11...
f5 {are alternative plans} 12. Qd2 h6 13. Nc2 g5 14. e3 Ng6 15. f4 $14) 12. Nc2
{[#]} ({It was more accurate to play in the center with} 12. f4 $1 Bh3 13. Bxh3
Qxh3 14. e4 $14) 12... Bh3 13. Qd2 $6 {Duda prepares b3-b4 break, but this
plan is simply too slow.} ({Instead, it was necessary to play on the kingside,
for example:} 13. Bxh3 Qxh3 14. Nce3 f5 15. f4 g5 $5) 13... Bxg2 14. Kxg2 f5
15. b4 $6 {White does not realize the danger.} ({This was the last opportunity
to slow down Black's pawn storm with} 15. e4 f4 16. f3 {even though Black
position already looks for preference.}) 15... f4 $1 {[%csl Yg2][%cal Yc2e3] A
strong attacking move worth remembering. It not only opens the f-file for the
rooks and c8-h3 diagonal for the queen, but also takes away e3 square from
white knight, thus cutting off support to the d5-knight.} 16. bxc5 dxc5 {
A structure similar to Aronian-Carlsen has arisen, but a clearly better
version for Black by comparison.} 17. e4 {White insists on keeping control of
d5-square, but this comes with a price - Black attack is in full swing now.} (
17. Nxe7+ Nxe7 18. f3 {was safer, but quite sad-looking for White after} Nf5
$17) 17... f3+ $40 18. Kh1 Nd4 19. Nxe7+ Qxe7 20. Ne3 Qd7 21. Bxd4 exd4 22. Nd5
Rbe8 23. Rg1 Qg4 $2 (23... Qh3 24. Qg5 Re5 25. Qh4 Qd7 26. g4 g5 27. Qg3 b5 $1
$19) 24. Qd1 $2 (24. Qa5 $1 Re5 25. Nf4 g5 26. Qc7 $1 $132) 24... Re5 25. Nf4
g5 26. h3 (26. Nd5 Re6 27. Qf1 Rh6 28. Ne7+ Kh8 29. Nf5 {radi} Rxf5 $1 30. exf5
Qh5 $19) 26... Qd7 27. Qxf3 Re7 28. Rg2 Qc7 29. Qh5 gxf4 30. gxf4 Qxf4 31. Qxc5
Qh4 32. Rg3 Kh8 33. Rag1 b6 34. Qd5 Qf4 35. c5 bxc5 36. Qxc5 Qe5 37. Qc6 Ref7
38. Rg5 Qf4 39. e5 Qxf2 40. Qe4 Re7 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

