-13,-15,-54,-67,-13,-22,-36,-36,1,67,79,51,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,-664,-1889,-29989,
-29990,-29995,-800,-800,-800,-800,-822] 7. Double fianchetto against King's
Indian defense with Nf6} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. g3 g6 3. b3 Bg7 4. Bb2 c5 5. Bg2 d6 6.
O-O e5 {[%csl Bb2][%cal Bd2d4] With this move, Black creates a bind against
the dark-squared bishop and controls d4-square. This is the most popular
strategy for Black against the double fianchetto in the KID these days.} 7. c4
O-O 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d3 {[%csl Bf6] With the knight on f6, Black has a slightly
more difficult time playing ...f5.} h6 10. Nd2 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Yd2e4,
Yc3d5] This maneuver is slightly different compared to Nf3-e1-c2 from the
previous game. The goal is to fight for e4 and d5 squares.} Be6 {[#]} 11. Rc1 {
A somewhat mysterious move.} ({A more natural continuation is} 11. Nde4 Ne8 12.
Nd5 {[%csl Gd5,Ge4][%cal Re4c3] when White gets good control over the central
squares.} Ne7 (12... Qd7 {similar to Duda-Grandelius, is a better version for
White after} 13. Nec3 Bh3 14. Bxh3 Qxh3 15. f4 f5 16. e4 Nf6 17. Qd2 $14 {
[%csl Bd5,Bc3]}) 13. Nec3 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Nc7 15. Nc3 {White prefers not to
exchange pieces.} Rb8 16. e3 d5 {[#] The critical moment. What would you play?}
17. Qc2 (17. e4 d4 18. Nd5 $14 {seems more to the point - White will get a
slight edge after the exchange on d5.} Nxd5 19. cxd5 Bd7 20. f4) 17... d4 18.
exd4 exd4 19. Ne4 {This structure is reminiscent of Maghsoodloo-Aronian. In
this game, the Iranian player makes a better case for it.} b6 20. Rae1 f5 21.
Nd2 g5 22. Nf3 Qd6 23. Bc1 f4 $6 {Perhaps too weakening.} 24. gxf4 gxf4 25. Kh1
$1 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Gf1g1,Gf3d2]} Rbe8 26. Nd2 Qd7 27. Rg1 Kh8 28. Bf3 Bf5 29.
Ne4 $14 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Gc2d1,Gf3g4]} Ne6 30. Qd1 Bxe4 31. Bxe4 Ng5 32. Rxg5
Rxe4 33. Rxe4 hxg5 34. Qh5+ $16 {1-0 (76) Maghsoodloo,P (2649)-Hakobyan,A  
(2554) Manavgat 2018}) (11. Nd5 {is not so accurate due to} Qd7 12. Nxf6+ Bxf6
13. Ne4 Bg7 14. Nc3 f5 $132) 11... Qd7 12. a3 Rac8 13. Nd5 b6 14. Bc3 {White
is spending too much time preparing b3-b4.} (14. e3 $13 {was better}) 14... Bg4
$1 {A good move, putting pressure on white kingside.} 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Ne4
Bg7 17. Bd2 $6 {Another time-wasting move. Black gets to carry out his pawn
break with the f-pawn now:} f5 18. Nc3 f4 $1 $36 19. Bd5+ Kh8 20. f3 Bh3 21.
Rf2 Ne7 22. Be4 Nf5 23. gxf4 exf4 24. Bxf4 Bd4 25. Nd5 Qg7 $1 26. Bd2 g5 $40
27. e3 g4 28. fxg4 Bxg4 29. Qe1 Bf3+ 30. Kf1 Nh4 31. exd4 Bg2+ 32. Ke2 Qg4+ 33.
Ke3 Bxe4 34. Bc3 Ng2+ 35. Kd2 Nxe1 36. dxc5+ Kg8 {0-1 White resigns.} 0-1

