272,275,245,254,245,251,240,232,231,260,245,247,234,238,239,241,240,240,229,
242,240,240,232,248,240,240,234,234,237,270,247,257,255,253,251,259,238,251,
242,250,242,242,242,629,726,722,992,1252,1262]} 1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. g3 d5 4.
Bg2 dxc4 5. Qa4+ c6 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2 Bb7 {Black is planning to activate his
light-squared bishop by means of ...Nbd7 followed by ...c6-c5. I think that
the best way to fight against this idea is} 8. a4 {By putting pressure on b5,
White makes difficult for Black to carry out the advance ...c6-c5.} ({Another
possible setup is} 8. O-O Nbd7 9. b3 {when the critical position arises after}
Be7 10. Bb2 O-O 11. d3 Qb6 12. Nbd2 c5 13. Rac1 Rac8 14. Qb1 {Black managed to
solve all his problems. The b7-bishop is now very active. On the other hand,
White's position is very solid and flexible. His main plan is to double the
rooks on the c-file and follow with a2-a3 followed by b3-b4, thus getting
access to the important d4-square. In many cases, especially when Black's
pieces are poorly coordinated, the advance d3-d4 is also possible. In the game
Bocharov - Shomoev, Black played} Nd5 {with the idea to exchange the
dark-squared bishops via f6.} ({Another thematic idea is} 14... Rfd8 15. a3 Nb8
{[%cal Gb8c6] In such structures, Black often tries to relocate his d7-knight
to c6.} 16. Rc2 Nc6 17. Rfc1 Nd7 18. e3 {[%cal Gd3d4] When the knight goes
away from the centre, preparing d3-d4 is the most logical approach.} ({Another
way to prepare d3-d4 would be} 18. Qa1 Bf8 19. d4 cxd4 20. Nxd4 Ne7 $11 {
After massive exchanges, Black will manage to comfortably equalize.}) 18... Nf8
19. d4 ({The move} 19. Ne1 $6 {was seen in the game ½-½ (27) Rusev,K (2556)
-Swapnil,S (2469) Varna 2013. Nevertheless, I consider it to be too passive.})
19... Nd7 ({In case of} 19... cxd4 20. Nxd4 Nxd4 21. Bxd4 Qa6 22. Rxc8 Bxc8 23.
Qc2 Bd7 24. Nb1 $14 {Despite the symmetrical pawn structure, White's active
pieces and Black's queenside weaknesses provide with a slight edge.}) 20. Ne4 {
White enjoys a slight pressure in this position.}) 15. a3 Bf6 {At this point,
White should have played} 16. Rc2 ({After} 16. e4 $6 Bxb2 17. Qxb2 Ne7 {
[%cal Ge7c6] Black was doing fine in the game ½-½ (44) Bocharov, D (2605)
-Shomoev,A (2557) Moscow 2011}) 16... Rc7 17. Ne4 Bxb2 18. Qxb2 h6 19. Rfc1
Rfc8 20. Ne5 {White has a very slight pressure due to the pressure on c5.
White can also consider the idea of pushing b3-b4. With a careful play,
however, Black should be able to maintain the equality without too much of a
problem.}) 8... a6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. Nc3 {[%csl Ga4,Gc3][%cal Ga4b5] This is a
very important move in White's setup. The construction Nc3+a4 makes it
difficult for Black to carry out the advance ...c6-c5.} Rc8 11. d3 Be7 12. e4 {
[%csl Rb7,Gd3,Ge4,Rf6] This is my preferred way of putting the central pawns.
Whenever Black manages to play ...c6-c5, his minor light-squared bishop and
f6-knight will be restricted by White's central pawn chain.} O-O 13. h3 {
[%csl Ge3][%cal Gc1e3] Securing the e3-square for the bishop.} Qb6 {[%cal
Gc6c5]} 14. Be3 c5 {In most of your games featuring this line, you will be
getting this pawn structure. White has two main ideas: 1) provoking the
weakening ...b5-b4 advance 2) carry out b2-b4 after axb5 In this game, Delchev
executed the advance b2-b4 in the most straightforward way -} 15. axb5 {
The next example will feature 15.Rfc1 which is a good preparatory move.} axb5
16. b4 {This is one of the main ideas behind White's setup. After playing a
move like Rfb1 or Qb2(b1), White will be threatening to recapture on c5. It
turns out that the b5-pawn is a major problem for Black.} Qc6 $6 {This is
already a step in the wrong direction. The c6-square is not suitable for the
queen.} ({In order to benefit from White's straightforward move order, Black
should have played} 16... Qd8 {when the following sequence is possible:} 17.
Nxb5 cxb4 18. Qd2 Nc5 19. Nbd4 Qd7 20. Rfb1 Ra8 21. Bf1 h6 22. Rxa8 Bxa8 23.
Rxb4 Nfxe4 24. dxe4 Nxe4 25. Qb2 Bxb4 26. Qxb4 Rc8 $132 {The position is
balanced.}) 17. Qb1 $1 {[%csl Rc6][%cal Gf1c1,Gc1c6] This precise move was
probably underestimated by Nisipeanu. White is planning to follow with Rfc1,
questioning the position of the black queen.} cxb4 18. Nd4 $1 {This was the
point behind 17.Qb1!} Qb6 $2 {After this move, White is getting a decisive
advantage.} ({Probably, Black should have tried the queen sacrifice -} 18...
Qxc3 19. Rc1 Rb8 20. Rxc3 bxc3 {Nevertheless, after} 21. Bf4 e5 22. Nf5 Bc5 23.
Be3 $16 {His compensation does not seem to be sufficient.}) 19. Nf5 Qd8 20.
Nxe7+ Qxe7 21. Nxb5 {[%cal Ga1a4] The b4-pawn looks doomed. Additionally,
White enjoys a powerful pair of bishops.} Ne5 22. Bd2 Nc6 23. Na7 $1 {Delchev
keeps making precise moves. White's advantage is obvious. Later Delchev
managed to win the game, despite the mutual inaccuracies.} Rb8 24. Rc1 Qd7 25.
Bf4 Ra8 26. Nxc6 Rxa1 27. Qxa1 Bxc6 28. Qb2 Qb7 29. Bd6 (29. Be5 Ra8 30. Rc4
$18) 29... Rd8 30. Qxb4 $2 Ne8 31. Qxb7 Bxb7 32. Bc5 Rxd3 $11 33. Rb1 Rd7 34.
e5 Bc8 35. Bc6 Rc7 36. Bxe8 Rxc5 37. Rb8 g6 38. Bd7 Rxe5 39. Rxc8+ Kg7 40. Rc7
Kf8 41. Rb7 h5 42. Rb5 Re1+ 43. Kg2 Rd1 44. Bc6 Rd2 45. Rc5 Rb2 46. Be4 Kg7 47.
Bc2 Rb4 48. Kf3 Kf6 49. Ke3 Rb7 50. Kd3 Ra7 51. Ke3 Ra3+ 52. Bd3 Ra7 53. g4
hxg4 54. hxg4 Ra3 55. g5+ Kg7 56. f3 Ra1 57. Kd4 Rg1 58. Bc4 Rg3 59. Ke3 Rg1
60. Bd3 Rg2 61. Bc4 Rg1 62. Kf2 Ra1 63. Rc7 Kf8 64. Rb7 Rc1 65. Bd3 Rc5 66. Rb5
Rc1 67. Ke3 Kg7 68. Ra5 Rg1 69. Kf2 Rc1 70. Bf1 Rd1 71. Ke2 Rc1 72. Bh3 Rc3 73.
Bg4 Kf8 74. Kd2 Rb3 75. Re5 Ra3 76. Ke2 Kg7 77. Kf2 Ra2+ 78. Ke3 Ra4 79. Kd3
Rb4 80. Ra5 Kf8 81. Kc3 Rf4 82. Kb3 Rd4 83. Re5 Kg7 84. Re4 Rd5 85. f4 Kf8 86.
Kc4 Ke7 87. Rd4 Ra5 88. Kb4 Ra2 89. Bd1 Ra1 90. Bc2 Rc1 91. Rc4 Re1 92. Re4 Rc1
93. Bb3 Rb1 94. Kc4 Rb2 95. Kc3 Rb1 96. Bc4 Rc1+ 97. Kd4 Rd1+ 98. Kc5 Rc1 99.
Kb6 Rb1+ 100. Bb5 Rb2 101. Kc6 Rc2+ 102. Rc4 Rxc4+ 103. Bxc4 f6 104. Bd3 e5
105. fxe5 1-0

