runs into} Qd8 17. Nb1 c4 $15 {when Black is already better.}) 16... a5 17.
Nbd2 Rfd8 18. Nc4 Qa7 19. Rd1 ({Similar is} 19. b3 {when Black solves his
problems by exchanging all the knights -} Nb6 20. Nfd2 Nxc4 21. Nxc4 Nd7 22.
Rd1 Nb6 23. Rac1 Nxc4 24. dxc4 Qa8 $11 {with equality.}) 19... Nb6 20. Nfd2
Nfd7 21. Rac1 Nxc4 22. Nxc4 Nb6 23. h4 {In positions with all the knights
exchanged, White's only practical chance is to initiate kingside play. A
possible line in which White can at least create some practical problems is} h5
24. Qe2 Nxc4 25. dxc4 Qa8 26. Qf3 g6 27. Qf4 Rxd1+ 28. Rxd1 Rd8 29. Rxd8+ Qxd8
30. b3 {Even though the position remains equal, Black should pay attention to
the weak dark squares around his king.}) 16. axb5 axb5 17. b4 {The same idea
we are already familiar with.} Nb8 $6 {[%cal Gb8a6] Planning to transfer the
knight to a6. If White plays precisely, however, this plan is not effective.} (
{In response to} 17... h6 {White can execute one of his thematic ideas in the
position -} 18. Qb2 {[%cal Ga1a5]} Rb8 19. Ra5 Bc6 20. Na2 $14 {[%cal Gf3d2,
Gd2b3] followed by Nd2-b3 with an annoying pressure.}) 18. Qb1 ({Even more
precise would have been} 18. Qe2 $1 {[%cal Gc1b1] planning Rcb1.} Nbd7 (18...
Na6 19. Rcb1 $16) 19. Rcb1 $16) 18... Na6 19. bxc5 Bxc5 20. d4 Be7 21. Qxb5 $2
{This move lets the advantage slip away.} ({White should have played} 21. Ne5
$1 {when a possible line would have been} b4 22. d5 Qc7 23. Nc6 bxc3 24. Bb6
