187,158,203,182,187,207,211,114,108,100,127,77,77,77,103,93,152,100,143,162,
179,149,194,214,319,280,29987,29988] In this example, we shall examine the
situation in which Black fails to exchange the knight after playing ...b5-b4.
The position of interest arises after} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 dxc4
5. Qa4+ c6 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. a4 b4 10. d3 c5 {We already
know that if Black manages to exchange the knights, he will be doing pretty
much OK in this structure. In order to achieve this exchange, Black will need
the b6-square. That's why Mirzoev played the thematic} 11. a5 $1 {preventing
Black from pushing ...a7-a5 himself.} Rc8 12. Nbd2 Be7 13. Nc4 {[%cal Gf3d2,
Gd2b3] With knights on the board, this structure is very difficult for Black.
On the other hand, White's plan is clear. After the manoeuvre Nfd2-b3, he will
start gaining space on the kingside.} Nd5 14. Nfd2 O-O 15. Nb3 Qc7 16. e4 N5f6
17. Bf4 {White wants to provoke the weakening ...e6-e5.} ({Of course, the
straightforward} 17. f4 {would have been a good option as well.}) 17... e5 18.
Be3 Ng4 {This move does not provide any benefit. In any case, the g4-knight is
rather unstable.} ({Better would have been} 18... Ba6 {when White can play} 19.
Rac1 Rfd8 20. Bh3 $14 {[%cal Gf2f4] with an annoying pressure. We can now see
the interest of provoking ...e6-e5. White's light-squared bishop get access to
the diagonal h3-c8. Additionally, the e5-pawn can be used as a hook for the
break f2-f4.}) 19. Bd2 Rcd8 20. Bh3 h5 21. f3 Ngf6 22. Be3 {[%cal Gc2f2]} ({
Even more precise would have been} 22. Ne3 $1 {[%cal Gd2b4,Ge3f5] creating two
annoying threats at once - Bxb4 and Nf5. After} Qb8 23. Nf5 Rfe8 24. Nxe7+ Rxe7
25. Be3 $16 {White's advantage is out of question.}) 22... h4 $2 {Black plays
into White's hand. Opening the h-file is just a suicide.} ({More tenacious
would have been} 22... Ba6) 23. Qf2 ({Once again, the move} 23. f4 {would have
been a decent option.}) 23... hxg3 24. hxg3 {White has a winning advantage.
His idea is simple - deliver mate along the h-file. Later on, Mirzoev managed
to convert his advantage.} Qc6 25. Rfc1 (25. Qh2 $18) 25... Ba6 26. Qh2 Bxc4
27. Rxc4 Nb6 28. axb6 Rxd3 29. Na5 Qb5 30. Bf1 Rxe3 31. Rc3 Re1 32. Rxe1 Qxa5
33. Rcc1 Qxb6 34. Bc4 g6 35. Qh6 Nh5 36. Kg2 Rd8 37. Red1 Rd4 38. Rxd4 exd4 39.
e5 Bf8 40. Qg5 Ng7 41. Kf2 Ne6 42. Qh4 a5 43. Rh1 Bg7 44. Qe7 Bf8 45. Qd7 b3
46. Qa4 Bg7 47. f4 g5 48. f5 Nc7 49. Qd7 1-0

