-81,-81,-38,-55,-70,-76,-67,-54,-77,-111,-87,-180,-180,-180,-217,-129,-313,
-351,-351,-354,-272,-253,-253,-293,-263,-363,-231] In this example, we will
focus on the most flexible way of handling this pawn structure with Black. The
critical position arises after} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2 dxc4 5.
Qa4+ c6 6. Qxc4 b5 7. Qc2 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Nc3 a6 10. a4 Rc8 11. d3 Be7 12.
e4 O-O 13. h3 a5 $1 {This flexible move is the favourite of the top-level
players. Black is planning to follow with ...Ba6. Afterwards, besides the
usual ...c5-c4, Black can also consider ...Nc5.} 14. Be3 Ba6 15. Rfd1 {This
natural move is not the most precise continuation.} ({My analysis shows that
White should have preferred} 15. Rfc1 $1 {The c1-square is the natural spot
for the rook in such positions. In the following variations, the reader can
see how useful the c1-rook is.} b4 {[%cal Gc6c5,Gd7b8,Gb8c6,Gc6d4] This is the
most straightforward continuation, but maybe not the most precise one. Black's
idea is ...c6-c5 followed by ...Nb8-c6-d4. With a white rook on c1, however,
it is not easy for Black to accomplish this plan.} ({Of course, Black could
start with} 15... Nb8 {when White will replay with the useful} 16. Bf1 {
And if Black keeps delaying ...b5-b4 with a move such as} h6 {White can opt for
} 17. axb5 cxb5 18. Qb1 {[%cal Gd3d4] planning d3-d4.} b4 19. Na4 $14 {White
is slightly better due to his strong central control and Black's weaknesses on
c5 and a5.}) ({Probably, Black's most precise move is the waiting} 15... h6 {
In this case, White's only constructive idea is} 16. Ne2 {[%cal Ge2d4] the
knight is heading for d4. Now, Black can already play} b4 {with the idea to
answer} 17. Ned4 {with} c5 {In my analysis, I went a bit further. Those who
are interested in having a high-level Reti repertoire can take a look at the
following sequence -} 18. Nb3 c4 19. dxc4 Rxc4 20. Qd1 Nxe4 21. Nfd4 Ndf6 22.
Rxc4 Bxc4 23. Rc1 Bd5 24. Nc6 Bxc6 25. Qxd8 Rxd8 26. Rxc6 Rd3 27. Nxa5 Nxg3 28.
fxg3 Rxe3 29. Kf2 Rd3 30. Nc4 Rd1 31. Bf3 Ra1 32. a5 Nd5 33. Ke2 $44 {Even
though Black is a pawn up, the strong a5-pawn makes White's position slightly
preferable.}) 16. Nb1 c5 17. Nbd2 Nb8 18. Bf1 h6 19. Nb3 $14 {We can now see
the point behind 15.Rfc1. Due to the pressure on c5, Black is unable to play ..
.Nc6. White enjoys a slight edge in this position.}) 15... b4 16. Nb1 c5 17.
Nbd2 Nb8 {Now, Black is in time to execute his desired manoeuvre.} 18. Nc4 Nfd7
19. Rac1 Nc6 20. Qb3 Qc7 21. Bf4 {This time, provoking ...e6-e5 does not help
White. Actually, Black would get better control of the d4-square.} e5 22. Bd2
Nd4 23. Nxd4 cxd4 {[%cal Gd7c5] Black's tremendous space advantage makes his
position preferable. He is ready to follow with ...Nc5. Bruzon managed to
convert his advantage.} 24. Bf1 Qd8 25. f4 exf4 26. Bxf4 Nc5 27. Qc2 g5 28. Bd2
f5 29. Be1 fxe4 30. dxe4 Rxf1+ 31. Kxf1 d3 32. Qf2 Nb3 33. Qf5 Nd4 34. Qd5+
Qxd5 35. exd5 Bxc4 36. Bf2 d2+ 0-1

