{[%evp 0,89,24,-16,-17,-17,-17,-29,-12,-12,6,6,-1,-1,26,-28,46,-20,0,0,0,0,0,
-7,-2,-2,14,-17,-5,18,23,13,24,26,28,29,42,42,42,42,45,52,48,51,51,49,51,4,7,7,
9,-15,-10,-4,11,22,21,21,17,8,15,12,30,39,35,44,34,45,36,57,37,42,29,39,65,72,
82,51,55,52,45,59,63,16,28,19,24,-8,-8,-2,-2,0] Now, we shall take a look at
another popular try for Black. After the moves} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 d5 3. Bg2 Nf6 4.
Nf3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ {instead of 5...c6, Black can try} Bd7 6. Qxc4 c5 {[%cal
Gd7c6,Gb8d7] The idea is simple. Black wants to comfortably develop his
queenside by means of ...Bc6 followed by ...Nbd7. Therefore, White should
immediately play} 7. Ne5 {when the main line goes} Qc8 8. Qd3 $1 {[%cal Ge5d7]
Remember this subtle positional move. White is planning to obtain the bishop
pair by means of Nxd7. With his last move, he anticipates 9...Qxd7 in response
to 9.Nxd7. After the eventual exchange of the queens, White's bishop pair will
provide an advantage in the arising endgame. The main line goes} Nc6 9. Nxd7
Nxd7 10. b3 Be7 11. Bb2 O-O 12. Nc3 {The position has clarified. Black has a
decent pawn structure, active pieces and no weaknesses. White's hopes of an
advantage are mainly related to the bishop pair. The flexible pawn structure
creates room for different pawn breaks. In the long run, this factor will only
increase the importance of the bishop pair. Of course, White should be ready
for a very long fight. The next few moves are quite logical.} Rd8 13. Rc1 Nf6
14. Qb1 Qd7 15. d3 Nd4 16. O-O Nd5 $1 {This is a key move in the position. In
positions with 2 bishops and a knight against two knights and a bishop, the
side playing with a bishop pair should try to keep his knight on the board. In
this way, the opponent will be unable to achieve a position with queen and
knight against queen and bishop. For example, in this position, Black wants to
exchange a pair of knights as well as the dark-squared bishops. In such a case,
Black can build his dark square strategy by using the tandem Q+N. Having in
mind all these considerations, one can easily understand the last move of
Grandelius. He is forcing wait to part with his remaining knight.} ({If Black
plays a natural waiting move such as} 16... Rac8 {, White will manage to keep
his knight -} 17. e3 Nc6 18. Rfd1 {[%cal Gc3e2] Now, ...Nd5 can always be met
with Ne2. White has an obvious advantage.}) 17. Rfe1 Nxc3 18. Bxc3 Rac8 19. e3
Nf5 20. Red1 {In the long run White will be trying to execute the idea a2-a3
followed by b3-b4, thus deflecting the c5-pawn and gaining better central
control. On the other hand, Black will keep making solid moves while trying to
exchange the dark-squared bishops.} b6 21. Qb2 Bf8 22. Qe2 Qe7 23. Rc2 {
[%cal Gd1c1] Doubling the rooks along the c-file will make the advance b3-b4
more effective.} g6 24. Rdc1 Qd7 25. Bf1 Bg7 26. Be1 {[%csl Ge1,Gf1] Putting
the bishops on the first rank in order to prevent exchanges is a typical
strategy in positions with a bishop pair. As we know, the bishop can actively
take part in the game even from the first rank.} Ne7 {[%cal Ge7d5]} 27. b4 {
Finally, White manages to carry out this typical pawn break.} cxb4 28. Bxb4
Rxc2 29. Rxc2 Nd5 30. Be1 Rc8 31. d4 Bf8 {Even though White is slightly better,
Black has a very solid position. Additionally, White should reckon with
Black's queenside majority.} 32. Rc4 a5 33. Rxc8 Qxc8 34. e4 {This move leads
to equality.} ({In my opinion, White should have tried to exchange the queens
by means of} 34. Qc4 {keeping a tiny edge.}) 34... Nb4 35. Qc4 Qxc4 36. Bxc4 a4
$6 (36... Nc2 37. Bc3 Bb4 38. Bb2 Ba3 $11) 37. Bd2 (37. f4 $5) 37... Nc2 38. d5
exd5 39. exd5 Nd4 40. Be3 Bc5 41. d6 Kf8 42. d7 Ke7 43. Bxd4 Bxd4 44. Bb5 a3
45. Kg2 1/2-1/2

