{The next example is a good illustration of White's strategy in positions
where Black tries to prevent the advance b3-b4 by means of ...a7-a5. Just like
in the game Cheparinov - Grandelius, in this position, Giri transferred his
queen to e2 -} 21. Qb2 Bf8 22. Qe2 g6 {[%cal Gf8g7]} 23. Be1 $1 {Once again,
we see this typical idea. White anticipates ...Bg7.} Qb5 24. Bf1 a5 {With this
move, Black is trying to prevent the advance b3-b4 at any cost. The drawback
of this strategy is that in some cases the b6-pawn might become a weakness.
After} 25. Rc2 Ne7 {Giri executed a must-know manoeuvre in this structure -}
26. Qg4 {[%cal Gg4a4] A very original idea. White wants to exchange the queens
via a4. After the eventual bxa4, White will be able to put pressure on b6
along the b-file. The game went} Qe8 27. Qa4 Nd5 28. Qxe8 Rxe8 29. a3 {The
exchange of the queens is clearly in White's favour. Now, he will be trying to
use his bishop pair and flexible pawn structure.} Ra8 30. Rb1 Reb8 31. Bd2 b5 {
Black does not want to stay in a passive position. Depending on the concrete
circumstances, he can either play ...a5-a4 or ...b5-b4. With a few precise
moves, Giri secures a stable edge.} 32. e4 Nf6 33. Bf4 Rb7 34. Be3 Nd7 35. e5 {
[%cal Gf1g2] Gradually, White's bishop pair is getting very powerful. This is
the so-called long term potential of the bishop pair.} Rd8 36. f4 Rbb8 37. Bg2
c4 {Going for simplifications is Black's best defensive strategy.} 38. dxc4
bxc4 39. Rxc4 Bxa3 40. Rd1 $6 {This move misses the advantage.} ({White should
have played} 40. Ba7 Rbc8 41. Rd1 Nf8 42. Rxd8 Rxd8 43. Be4 $14 {Keeping his
edge.}) 40... Nf8 41. Rxd8 Rxd8 42. Be4 Rb8 43. Bc2 Nd7 44. Rc7 Nb6 45. Be4 Nd5
46. Bxd5 exd5 47. Bd4 Kf8 48. Bc5+ Bxc5+ 49. Rxc5 Rxb3 50. Rxa5 Rd3 51. Kf2
Rd2+ 52. Ke3 Rxh2 53. Rxd5 h5 54. Rd7 Rg2 55. Kf3 Rb2 56. Ra7 Rb3+ 57. Kf2 Rb2+
1/2-1/2

