{[%evp 0,61,26,-21,-4,-42,-7,-12,-11,-9,-9,0,-7,-1,-6,10,34,42,49,51,51,46,36,
46,51,56,90,72,72,72,80,77,131,99,113,113,133,106,155,159,159,172,186,224,195,
207,210,159,159,171,174,181,297,217,200,219,244,209,257,235,263,263,247,246]
It's time to take a look at another major possibility for Black. After the
usual moves} 1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 e6 3. Bg2 d5 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Qa4+ {Black often goes
} Nbd7 {which is a flexible way to develop the queenside. If given the
possibility, Black is planning to proceed with ...a7-a6 followed by ...b7-b5
and ...Bb7. Contrary to the systems based on ...c7-c6, in this case, he will
play ...c7-c5 in one move. Of course, if White knows the right move order,
Black will not manage to reach this perfect setup.} 6. Qxc4 a6 7. Qc2 {White
anticipates the advance ...b7-b5. If Black goes for it now, White will answer
with the simple 8.Nd4 with a winning position.} c5 8. Nc3 $1 {It's very
important to play Nc3 before 0-0. As it will become clear, this is a
prophylactic against ...b7-b5.} Be7 $2 {Strangely enough, this natural
developing move is probably the main reason for Black's defeat in this game.} (
{In this position, the thematic} 8... b5 $2 {runs into} 9. Ne5 $1 {when Black
cannot close the long diagonal by means of ...Nd5. This was the point behind 8.
Nc3.}) ({The right move would have been} 8... Qc7 {preparing the advance of
the b-pawn. This continuation will be dealt with in the next example.}) 9. O-O
O-O 10. d4 ({Maybe even more price would have been} 10. Rd1 {[%cal Gd2d4,Gd1d8]
The idea is that after} b5 $2 11. Ne5 $18 {White is winning because there is
no hanging pawn on d4.}) 10... cxd4 $2 {After this mistake, Black is
positionally lost.} ({The last chance would have been} 10... b5 11. Ne5 Nxe5
12. dxe5 Nd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Be3 $16 {White has an obvious advantage.
Nevertheless, Black can still fight.}) 11. Nxd4 Qc7 12. Rd1 {[%csl Gg2] This
is the dream position of the Catalan players. Due to the pressure along the
diagonal h1-a8, Black cannot develop his queenside. White's advantage is close
to decisive.} ({Another idea was} 12. Be3 Ne5 13. Rac1 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1c7]
immediately questioning the badly placed c7-queen. The idea is to answer} Bd7 {
with} 14. Nd5 $18) 12... Rd8 13. Be3 Nb6 14. Rac1 e5 15. Nf5 Bxf5 16. Qxf5 $18
Nc4 17. Bg5 Rxd1+ 18. Nxd1 Rd8 19. Bxf6 Bxf6 20. Be4 Qa5 21. Nc3 Kf8 22. Nd5 b5
23. Qxh7 Rxd5 24. Bxd5 Qd2 25. Rxc4 bxc4 26. e4 Qxb2 27. Qh8+ Ke7 28. Qc8 Qb6
29. Qxc4 Qb5 30. Qc7+ Qd7 31. Qc5+ 1-0

