{The following game is a critical test for Black's concept. The first 8 moves
repeat the previous example -} 1. c4 e6 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. Nf3 dxc4 5. Qa4+
Nbd7 6. Qxc4 a6 7. Qc2 c5 8. Nc3 {At this point, Nepomniachtchi played the
correct} Qc7 {Now, White cannot stop Black from developing his light-squared
bishop. Of course, everything comes at a price. The black queen is not
optimally placed on c7. White can use it by means of} 9. d4 b6 10. Bf4 {
The critical position arises after the following natural sequence:} Bd6 11.
Bxd6 Qxd6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rfd1 O-O {It becomes obvious that the central pawns
will be exchanged. If White cannot immediately generate some activity, Black
will comfortably arrange his pieces. The best plan for White is gaining
central space with} 14. e4 cxd4 15. Nxd4 Qc7 16. Rac1 {In this pawn structure,
White's hopes for an advantage are mainly based on the advance e4-e5. At this
point, Black faces a choice between two main moves - 16...Rac8 and 16...Rad8.
In this game (the latest one), the World Championship contender played} Rac8 {
[%cal Gf8d8] Black is planning to comfortably put his rooks on c8 and d8. The
queen will go to b8. The drawback is that in some lines the advance ...e6-e5
will be answered with Nf5, threatening Ne7+.} ({After} 16... Rad8 17. Qe2 ({
The idea of putting the rook on d8 can be seen in the line} 17. f4 e5 {Now,
Nf5 does not create any problem for Black. White should simplify into a
drawish endgame -} 18. Nd5 Qxc2 19. Nxc2 exf4 20. gxf4 Nc5 21. Nce3 Bxd5 $2 {
This is a mistake. Now, White will get a strong passed pawn.} ({After the
correct} 21... Ncxe4 22. Nxb6 Rxd1+ 23. Nxd1 Rd8 $11 {The position is
objectively equal.}) 22. exd5 $16 {1-0 (51) Giri,A (2779)-Karjakin,S (2748)
Riga 2019}) 17... Qb8 {This position was reached in the game Donchenko -
Esipenko, 2021. White should have played} 18. b4 $5 {taking the c5-square from
the black knight. Later on, White can improve his position by means of Qe3
followed by Nb3. If Black plays ...b6-b5 with the idea to put his d7-knight to
c4, White can always answer with a2-a4.} ({After} 18. e5 Bxg2 19. exf6 Ba8 20.
fxg7 Kxg7 21. Ne4 Ne5 $132 {Black has enough counterplay on the light squares.}
) ({The move} 18. Rc2 {was played in the game: 0-1 (42) Donchenko,A (2668)
-Esipenko,A (2677) Wijk aan Zee 2021. Nevertheless, this approach seems too
passive.})) 17. f4 $1 {With a rook on c8, this move is critical.} Rfd8 {
Black is forced to allow e4-e5.} ({This time, after} 17... e5 $2 {White can
play} 18. Nf5 {[%cal Gf5e7] when Black should accept the ending arising after}
Qc5+ 19. Qf2 Qxf2+ 20. Kxf2 $16 {White has a clear advantage.}) 18. e5 Ng4 19.
Bxb7 Qxb7 20. Qe2 h5 21. h3 Nh6 22. Qxh5 {It seems that Black does not have
enough compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} Nc5 23. Qf3 {Svidler plays the
most reliable move.} ({Another option would have been} 23. Qh4 b5 24. g4 {
[%csl Rh6] leaving the h6-knight out of play. On the other hand, Black cannot
use the slightly weakened white king.}) 23... Qxf3 24. Nxf3 Nf5 25. Ne2 $16 {
The position has been clarified. We can say that Black does not have enough
compensation for the pawn. Due to the quick time control, Svidler didn't
manage to convert his advantage.} Ne3 26. Rxd8+ Rxd8 27. b4 (27. Ned4) 27...
Ne4 28. g4 b5 29. Ned4 Nd5 30. f5 exf5 31. gxf5 Nxb4 32. Rc7 Nd5 33. Ra7 Nf4
34. Rxa6 Nxh3+ 35. Kh2 Nf4 36. e6 fxe6 37. Nxe6 Nxe6 38. Rxe6 Nd2 39. Kg2 Nxf3
40. Kxf3 Ra8 41. Rb6 Rxa2 42. Rxb5 Ra6 43. Kf4 g6 44. fxg6 Rxg6 45. Rg5 Kh7 46.
Rxg6 Kxg6 1/2-1/2

