{Now, we shall start dealing with the lines in which Black refrains from ...
dxc4. The first 2 games feature the importance of the c6-square in symmetrical
positions (with exchanged central pawns).} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 d5 4. Bg2
Be7 ({As I have mentioned in the introduction, Black can go for Benoni
structures by means of} 4... d4 {Even though Benoni positions are not our
priority here, for the sake of completeness, I will suggest an easy and
playable setup for White. The main position of interest arises after} 5. O-O c5
6. e3 Nc6 7. exd4 cxd4 8. d3 {For those of you who don't have any experience
in Benoni I will briefly explain the main ideas for both sides. White is
usually looking for active play on the queenside. One of his main positional
ideas is to execute the advance b2-b4. On the other hand, Black will combine
his central play with pressure on the d3-pawn. Very often he tries to carry
out the advance ...e5-e4. Having less space, White will gladly start
exchanging minor pieces. Ideally, he would like to exchange a pair of knights
and get rid of the useless dark-squared bishop.} Bd6 {This is the most popular
move in the position. Black wants to take the e5-square under control. With
this move, he also supports the advance ...e6-e5.} ({After} 8... Be7 9. Re1 {
[%cal Gf3e5] White takes the control of e5 and can consider exchanging a pair
of knights by means of Ne5.}) {At this point, I would like to suggest the
following scheme:} 9. Na3 O-O 10. Nc2 e5 11. b4 {By using the slightly
vulnerable e5-pawn, White manages to carry out this thematic advance. Of
course, everything comes at a price. The knight is usually better placed on d2
than on c2. On the other hand, however, besides supporting b2-b4, to some
extent, the c2-knight discourages the break ...e5-e4. The position is unclear
and full of potential.}) 5. O-O O-O 6. b3 b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 8. cxd5 ({In the next
games, we will take a look at} 8. e3 {which is White's main move in the
position.}) 8... Nxd5 ({To the different pawn structure leads} 8... exd5 9. d4
{When the black bishop is already on b7, this pawn structure is always better
for White. Sooner or later, Black will have to play ...c7-c5, which can
eventually lead to the formation of hanging pawns. Black's main problem is
that White can make a number of useful moves before playing dxc5. For example,
such moves are Nc3, Rc1, e3, Nc2-e2-f4 and so on. At the same time, Black
cannot release the tension in a favourable way.}) 9. d4 c5 ({Safer looks} 9...
Nd7 10. Nc3 c5 {e.g.} 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Nxd5 Bxd5 13. Qd3 cxd4 14. Bxd4 Rxc1 15.
Rxc1 {1-0 Smyslov,V-Simagin,V/Moscow 1966/EXT 2002 (46)} Nc5 16. Qc3 f6 $11)
10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. Nbd2 Nd7 12. a3 {[%cal Gb3b4]} N5f6 {Black prevents e2-e4,
but allows White to gain space on the queenside.} ({Was possible} 12... a5 {
,not fearing} 13. e4 N5f6 14. e5 {in view of} Ne4 15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Qe2 Bd5 17.
Nd2 Bxg2 18. Kxg2 Qe7 19. Ne4 Rfd8 $11 {1/2-1/2 Razuvaev,Y (2510)-Klovans,J  
(2480)/Tbilisi 1973/MCD (32)}) 13. b4 Be7 14. Nd4 $1 {White discovers a weak
point in Black´s position - the c6-square.} Bxg2 15. Kxg2 {[%csl Rc6][%cal
Gd4c6]} Qc7 16. Qb3 {[%cal Gf1c1,Gb3f3]} Rfc8 ({Probably stronger was} 16...
Rac8 $5 17. Rfc1 Qb7+ 18. Qf3 Nd5 19. e4 N5f6 20. b5 Nb8 {,preventing Nd4-c6.})
17. Rfc1 Qb7+ 18. Qf3 Nd5 ({White also maintains the initiative in case of} 
18... Qxf3+ 19. N2xf3) 19. e4 N5f6 20. b5 $1 {Already threatening Nc6.} a6 $2 {
A serious mistake.} ({Was necessary to exchange the rooks by} 20... Ne5 21. Qe2
Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Rc8 {because after} 23. Rxc8+ (23. Rd1 $5 Ned7 24. Nc6 Nb8 25.
Nxe7+ Qxe7 $14) 23... Qxc8 24. f4 Ned7 {the invasion on c6 is less dangerous
for Black,for example:} 25. Nc6 Bf8 26. Qc4 (26. Nxa7 $6 Qc2 27. Bxf6 Nxf6 {
[%cal Gf6e4,Gf8a3]}) 26... Qa8 (26... Nc5 $143 27. Bxf6 gxf6 28. Qd4 a6 29. a4
axb5 30. axb5 $14) 27. a4 (27. Bxf6 Nxf6 28. Qa4 Qb7 $1 {[%cal Gb7d7]} 29. e5
Qd7 30. Nf3 Qd3 $1 $11 {[%cal Gd3e2]}) (27. e5 Nd5 28. Qa4 a5) (27. Qa4 a5 28.
bxa6 Nc5 29. Qb5 Qxa6) 27... Ne8 {and it is not easy for White to prove the
superiority of his position.}) 21. Nc6 Bf8 22. a4 axb5 23. axb5 Rxa1 24. Rxa1
Ra8 25. Rd1 $1 {White´s rook is more active and therefore White avoids the
exchange. The knight on c6 makes Black´s defensive task very difficult.} Ne8
$2 {This is not good, but Black is almost in Zugzwang.} ({Bad was} 25... Ra4 $2
26. e5 Nd5 27. Nd8) ({and if} 25... Ra2 $6 {then} 26. Nc4 Ra4 $140 $2 27. e5 $1
{[%cal Gc6e7]} Nd5 28. Nd8 Qa8 (28... Qc8 29. Qxf7+ Kh8 30. Qxe6) 29. Qxf7+ Kh8
30. Nc6) ({perhaps the only way to continue the fight was} 25... h6 26. Nc4 Qc7
$16) 26. Nc4 Nc5 27. e5 $1 {[%cal Gf3b7]} Rc8 $2 ({Loses immediately but also
after} 27... Nc7 $2 {White exploits the opposition between queens by} 28. Rd7
$1 Nxd7 29. Ne7+ Bxe7 30. Qxb7 $18) 28. Ra1 $1 {[%cal Ga1a7] With decisive
threats of Ra7 because Black has not Ra8.} Rc7 29. Ra7 Qxa7 30. Nxa7 Rxa7 31.
Nxb6 1-0

