{Even with a very little material on the board, the c6-knight can be very
annoying. Let's take a look at an example.} 1. c4 c5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Nc3 e6 4. g3
b6 5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Be7 7. b3 O-O 8. Bb2 d5 ({Another possible reaction for
Black is} 8... d6 9. e3 Nbd7 10. Qe2 a6 11. Rfd1 Qc7 ({or} 11... Ne4) 12. Rac1
(12. d4 Rfe8) 12... Ne4 13. Nb1 b5 14. d3 Nef6 $11 {1/2-1/2 Hort,V (2580)
-Gavrikov,V (2535)/Lugano 1989/TD (29)}) 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 Bxd5 11. Qb1 {
Prepares Rd1 and prevents Nc6 because of e2-e4.} Bf6 ({To the equality leads} 
11... Nd7 12. Rd1 Qc7 13. d4 Qb7 14. dxc5 Nxc5 $11) 12. Rd1 Bxb2 13. Qxb2 Nd7 (
{Also playable is} 13... Nc6 14. d3 (14. d4 $6 Qf6) 14... Bxf3 15. Bxf3 Rc8 16.
Bg2 Qd6 17. a3 Rc7 18. Rac1 Rfc8 19. e3 h6 $11 {0-1 Larsen,B-Smejkal,J/
Reykjavik 1978/EXT 98 (48)'}) 14. d4 Qc8 (14... Qf6 $6 15. Ne5) (14... Qc7 $142
) 15. dxc5 Nxc5 16. Ne5 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Rd8 ({Worse is} 17... Qb7+ 18. f3 Rad8
19. b4 Na4 ({not} 19... Nd7 $2 20. Qd4 $1 Nxe5 21. Qxd8) 20. Qc2 b5 21. Qc6 $14
) ({or} 17... f6 18. Nc4 Qc6+ 19. f3 b5 20. Na5 Qb6 21. b4 Na4 22. Qb3 Rac8 23.
Rd3 $14) ({but was also possible} 17... a5 18. Rd6 $140 f6 19. Nc4 b5 20. Nb6
$2 Qc7 21. Qd4 Rad8 22. Rd1 Nb7 23. Rd7 Rxd7 24. Nxd7 Rd8) 18. b4 Ne4 $2 {
Allows white knight to penetrate on c6-square.} ({White keeps some initiative
after} 18... Na4 $6 19. Qb3 Qb7+ (19... Qc3 20. Nxf7 $1 Qc6+ 21. f3 Kxf7 22. b5
) 20. f3 b5 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 22. Rd1) ({was necessary to choose between} 18...
Nd7 19. Rac1 $140 Qb7+ 20. Nc6 Nc5 $1 21. b5 a6 $1 ({dubious is} 21... Rxd1 $6
22. Rxd1 a6 {because of} 23. a4 $1 Nxa4 $140 $2 24. Qd4 $18 {[%cal Gd4d8,Gd4a4]
}) 22. Rxd8+ Rxd8 23. f3 Ra8 $11) ({and} 18... Qb7+ 19. f3 Nd7 20. Nc4 (20. Qd4
$6 Nf8 21. Qxd8 $2 Rxd8 22. Rxd8 Qc7 $19) 20... Nf6 $11) 19. Rxd8+ Qxd8 20. Nc6
$1 Qd7 21. Qc2 Nc5 22. b5 {Despite of reduced material White has clear better
prospects due to his Nc6.} Qb7 23. Rd1 a6 24. a4 Re8 25. f3 Qa8 (25... h6) 26.
Rd4 axb5 27. axb5 e5 $6 {Looking for some counterplay in passive situation,but
this advance only weakens Black´s position.} (27... h6 $142) 28. Rd5 e4 $2 {
Here the pawn becomes vulnerable.} (28... f6 $142) 29. f4 h6 30. Qc4 e3 ({
Wrong is} 30... Qa1 $2 31. Rf5 Re6 32. Nd8 Rf6 33. Nxf7 $1) ({and after} 30...
Qb7 {when White can continue} 31. Rd6 Qc7 32. Qd5 $16 {[%cal Gc6e5]}) 31. Rf5
Qb7 ({If} 31... Re6 {then} 32. Rxf7 $1 Kxf7 33. f5 Qe8 34. fxe6+ Nxe6 35. Qd5
$16) 32. Qd5 Ne4 $2 {The final mistake.} (32... Qd7 33. Qxd7 Nxd7 34. Rd5 $16 (
34. Kf3 Nf6 35. Re5 $16)) 33. Re5 Rxe5 34. Qxe5 Nc5 35. Qe8+ $1 ({Not giving
Black a chance to activate his queen in case of} 35. Qxe3 Qd7) 35... Kh7 36.
Kf3 $18 Ne6 37. Kxe3 Qc7 38. Kf3 Qd6 39. Ne7 $1 {Forcing the exchange of
queens.} Qd8 40. Qxd8 Nxd8 41. Ke4 1-0

[Event "Dortmund Sparkassen"]
[Site "Dortmund GER"]
[Date "2013.08.01"]
[Round "6"]
[White "Vladimir Kramnik"]
[Black "Daniel Grigoryevich Fridman"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A13"]
[WhiteElo "2784"]
[BlackElo "2629"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "67"]
[EventDate "2013.07.26"]

{In this game, we will cover the most important structures in the so-called
Neo-Catalan in which White goes for a double fianchetto without committing to
d2-d4. The main position arises after the moves} 1. c4 e6 2. Nf3 d5 3. b3 Nf6
4. g3 Be7 5. Bg2 O-O 6. O-O c5 7. Bb2 Nc6 8. e3 b6 9. Nc3 {Now, Black faces a
choice. In this game, Fridman went for} dxc4 {immediately releasing the
central tension. This is probably the best continuation.} ({The main
alternative is} 9... Bb7 {when White should play} 10. cxd5 {Opening the centre
is the best way to make use of the slightly more active pieces. Black should
recapture with a piece.} Nxd5 ({As we have already pointed out, the structure
arising after} 10... exd5 11. d4 {is clearly favourable for White.}) 11. Nxd5
Qxd5 (11... exd5 12. d4) 12. d4 {[%cal Gf3e5] Now, Black should find a way to
deal with the annoying threat of Ne5. The most popular move in the position is}
Rad8 ({Putting the other rook on d8 will weaken the f7-square. White can
exploit this drawback by means of} 12... Rfd8 $6 13. Ne5 Qd6 14. Qf3 $1 {
when Black will be forced to play} Nxe5 15. Qxb7 Nd3 16. Ba3 $16 {with an
obvious advantage for White.}) ({The move} 12... Na5 {is well met by} 13. dxc5
Bxc5 14. Qe2 {The superior piece activity gives White better chances in this
symmetrical position.}) ({A popular try is} 12... Qf5 {This move is the
favourite of GM Lenier Domingues. Of course, White should go for the bishop
pair with} 13. Ne5 Nxe5 14. Bxb7 {Even though Black is close to equality, I
believe that the bishop pair gives White a slight edge. You shall take a look
at the following variations.} Rad8 (14... Rab8 15. Bg2 cxd4 16. Bxd4 Rfd8 17.
Qe2 Bf6 18. Rfd1 $14) 15. Qe2 Qd3 16. Ba6 (16. Qh5 Qc2 17. Ba3 Nd3 18. Qd1 $14)
16... Qxe2 17. Bxe2 cxd4 18. Bxd4 Nc6 19. Bc3 $14) ({After} 12... Nb4 {White's
best option is to simplify into a slightly better symmetrical endgame arising
after} 13. Nh4 Qd7 14. dxc5 Qxd1 15. Rfxd1 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 Bxc5 17. a3 Nc6 18. b4
Be7 19. Rac1 $14 {White has a slight advantage due to his more active pieces
and Black's weakened queenside.}) 13. Ne5 Qd6 {The most reasonable option.} ({
Practice has shown that after} 13... Qxg2+ 14. Kxg2 Nxe5+ 15. f3 cxd4 16. exd4
Nc6 17. Rc1 {Black does not have enough compensation for the queen.½-½ (90)
Kramnik,V (2793)-Ezat,M (2454) Antalya 2013}) 14. dxc5 Qxc5 15. Nd7 {This move
marks the beginning of a forced sequence which is known to be favourable for
White. Below, I provide the critical lines.} Qf5 (15... Qg5 16. h4 Qh6 17. Rc1
e5 (17... Nb8 18. Rc7) 18. Qg4 Rfe8 19. Rfd1 $18) 16. e4 Qg5 17. h4 Qh6 18. Bc1
g5 19. hxg5 Qg7 (19... Bxg5 20. f4 Qg7 $1 21. fxg5 Qxa1 22. Nf6+ Qxf6 23. gxf6
Rxd1 24. Rxd1 Rd8 25. Rxd8+ Nxd8 26. Ba3 $16) 20. e5 Kh8 21. Bf4 Bxg5 22. Bxg5
Qxg5 23. Nxf8 Rxd1 24. Raxd1 $16 {1-0 (38) Miroshnichenko,E (2618)-Nakhbayeva,
G (2378) Al Ain 2014}) ({The move} 9... Ba6 {is well met by} 10. Nb5 {[%cal
Gd1e2,Gf1d1,Gd2d4] White's main idea will be to open the position with Qe2
followed by Rfd1 and d2-d4.}) 10. bxc4 Qd3 {This is not the most precise move.
Black plays into White's hand since the move Ne1 will be useful in any case.} (
{More to the point would have been} 10... Bb7 11. Qe2 Rc8 12. Rad1 Qc7 13. Ne1
{[%cal Gf2f4,Gg3g4,Gg4g5,Gc3e4] This move introduces White's classical plan in
such structures. He is planning to organize a kingside attack by means of
f2-f4 followed by g3-g4-g5 and Ne4. Of course, the manoeuvre Rf3-h3 is always
on the agenda. Black's best antidote is} Ne8 $1 {[%cal Ge8d6] d6 is the best
square for the knight in this pawn structure. Besides controlling f5, Black
also supports the advance ...b6-b5 which is the cornerstone of his counterplay.
The game might continue} 14. f4 Nd6 15. Nf3 a6 {[%cal Gb6b5]} 16. a4 {[%cal
Gg3g4,Gf4f5,Gg4g5]} f5 17. d3 Bf6 {With a complex fight to follow. White will
prepare the advance g3-g4 while Black will be trying to carry out ...b6-b5.})
11. Ne1 Qd7 12. Qe2 Bb7 13. f4 {Kramnik immediately goes for this classical
plan. The next few moves are obvious.} Rfd8 14. Rd1 Nb4 15. d3 Bxg2 16. Nxg2 a6
{[%cal Gb6b5] Black prepares the thematic ...b6-b5.} ({Of course, the move} 
16... Nxd3 $4 {[%cal Gd1d8] loses to} 17. Ne1 $18) 17. a3 Nc6 18. g4 $1 Ne8 {
It's already too late for this thematic move.} ({Preparing . ..b6-b5 does not
help either. Here is how White can develop his attack in this case -} 18...
Rab8 {[%cal Gf4f5,Gg4g5]} 19. g5 ({Another dangerous idea is} 19. f5 b5 20.
cxb5 axb5 21. g5 Ne8 22. g6 $5 (22. fxe6 fxe6 (22... Qxe6 23. Nf4 Qf5 24. h4 {
[%cal Gf1f8]}) 23. Ne4 {[%cal Ge2f3] With a dangerous attack.})) 19... Ne8 20.
Rf3 Nd6 21. Rh3 {[%csl Rh7][%cal Ge2h5]} g6 22. Qf2 b5 23. cxb5 axb5 24. Rxh7
Kxh7 25. Qh4+ Kg8 26. Nd5 $18 {[%cal Ga1h8]}) 19. f5 $1 {Since the Black
knight is heading for f5, this is the most precise way to attack. One of the
main ideas is to weaken the d5-square.} Nd6 (19... e5 {[%csl Rd5]} 20. Nd5 $16
{[%csl Gd5]}) (19... Bf6 20. fxe6 Qxe6 (20... fxe6 21. Nf4 {[%cal Gf4h5]} (21.
Ne4 Bxb2 22. Qxb2)) 21. Nf4 {[%csl Gd5] After installing a knight on d5, White
enjoys a huge advantage.}) 20. f6 $1 {A beautiful positional exchange
sacrifice. White's advantage is already decisive.} Bxf6 21. Rxf6 gxf6 22. Nf4 {
[%cal Ga1h8,Gf4h5,Gc3e4]} Ne5 (22... Kf8 23. Nh5 Ne8 24. Ne4) 23. Nh5 Qe7 24.
Rf1 Nd7 25. Qg2 h6 26. h4 Kf8 27. Qg3 Ke8 28. Qf4 (28. Na4 Rab8 29. Rxf6 Nxf6
30. Nxf6+ Kf8 31. Qf4 Qb7 32. Qxh6+ Ke7 33. Qg5 $18) 28... Qf8 (28... Rdb8 29.
Qxh6 b5) 29. Nd5 exd5 30. Bxf6 Ne5 (30... Nxf6 31. Nxf6+ Ke7 32. Qe5#) (30...
dxc4 31. Ng7+) 31. Qxe5+ Kd7 32. Bg7 Re8 33. Nf6+ Kc7 34. Qa1 1-0

