{[%evp 0,83,38,-3,-11,-38,8,0,-4,-9,18,4,33,18,32,24,14,25,25,-14,-15,3,9,26,
36,17,60,79,68,61,83,61,107,63,61,79,73,80,76,59,50,35,46,0,0,0,0,0,0,0,8,29,
54,54,107,46,60,66,65,52,75,73,137,131,124,119,113,131,118,118,292,303,296,288,
331,334,347,390,596,589,637,643,599,620,29991,29992]} 1. c4 Nf6 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2
d5 4. Nf3 Bg4 {Very popular system. Black is developing the bishop before
playing e6. There is a discussion which square is better: "g4" or "f5". My
preferences are for 4...Bg4, but they are both quite playable.} 5. Ne5 {
This is the most ambitious reply.} Bh5 $6 {This natural move is mistake. White
is gaining advantage after the following sequence:} (5... Be6 {Is the
strongest move here. More about it, you can see in the next game.}) (5... Bf5 {
is pretty much the same as Bh5} 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Nc3 e6 8. Qa4+ Nbd7 9. g4 Bc2
10. Nxf7 Kxf7) 6. cxd5 cxd5 7. Nc3 e6 8. Qa4+ Nbd7 9. g4 $1 {That's the
problem with 5...Bh5 (or Bf5), White is gaining a few tempos by attacking the
bishop.} Bg6 10. h4 Bc2 {This looks like a clever trick, and Black is OK if
White takes the bishop.} (10... Bd6 {is possible, but after} 11. d4 {White is
renewing the threat "h4 - h5"}) (10... h6 {is the most popular reply, but
White is much better after the simple.} 11. Nxg6 fxg6 12. g5 {1-0 (51)
Pantsulaia,L (2553)-Saydaliev,S (2384) Chess.com INT 2020}) 11. Nxf7 $1 (11.
Qxc2 Nxe5 $13) 11... Bxa4 12. Nxd8 Kxd8 13. Nxa4 Nxg4 14. Bh3 $16 {The rest is
simple technique and I leave it without comments.} Ndf6 15. d4 Rc8 16. Nc5 Bxc5
17. dxc5 Ne5 18. Rg1 g6 19. Bf4 Ned7 20. Bxe6 Rxc5 21. Be3 Rc6 22. Bh3 Re8 23.
Rd1 Rc2 24. Rd2 Rc1+ 25. Rd1 Rc2 26. h5 Rxb2 27. hxg6 hxg6 28. Rxg6 Rxa2 29.
Kf1 Rh8 30. Bg2 Ke7 31. Bxd5 Nxd5 32. Rxd5 Rh7 33. Bg5+ Kf7 34. Rgd6 Ke8 35.
Re6+ Kf8 36. Bh6+ Rxh6 37. Rxh6 Nb6 38. Rc5 Kg7 39. Rd6 Kf8 40. Rc7 Ke8 41.
Rxb7 Nc4 42. Rh6 1-0

