{[%evp 0,111,40,12,12,-7,-1,-8,12,-3,8,9,21,4,-4,15,25,25,22,22,41,14,40,46,32,
40,45,42,34,42,54,54,71,78,69,69,47,71,71,34,72,65,78,84,85,89,79,90,94,95,95,
95,115,55,63,68,73,70,121,65,73,65,107,95,94,97,108,125,120,110,134,138,133,
132,171,172,182,168,219,208,219,201,222,217,208,208,209,209,176,189,172,138,
146,181,180,152,148,189,188,120,109,116,110,120,219,230,242,242,259,259,270,
277,290,292]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 {Another system which is quite popular,
Black is developping his bishop at his first chance.} 3. Bg2 e6 4. O-O Nd7 {
This is a tricky move order, which doesn't allow 5.c4} 5. d4 (5. c4 $6 Bxf3 6.
Bxf3 Ne5 {is very good for Black.}) 5... c6 6. Nbd2 Ngf6 (6... f5 {was tried
by Beliavsky in his famous game against V.Kramnik} 7. c4 Bd6 8. Qb3 Rb8 9. Re1
Nh6 10. cxd5 cxd5 11. h3 Bh5 (11... Bxf3 12. exf3 $1 $18 {[%csl Re6]}) 12. e4
$3 {textbook blow in the centre. White is winning in all variations} fxe4 13.
Ng5 Bf7 (13... Qxg5 14. Nxe4 Qe7 15. Bg5 Qf8 16. Qxd5 $3 exd5 17. Nxd6# {
beautiful line}) (13... O-O 14. Nxe6 Qa5 15. Nxf8 Rxf8 16. Rxe4 $18) 14. Ndxe4
dxe4 15. Nxe6 Bxe6 16. Qxe6+ Qe7 17. Rxe4 Kd8 18. Qd5 {1-0 (18) V.Kramnik-A.
Beliavsky Belgrade 1995}) 7. Re1 {White's idea is simple. He wants to play e4
with a symbolic advantage.} Be7 8. e4 dxe4 (8... O-O {I like more than a plan
without taking on e4.} 9. c3 Rc8 10. e5 Ne8) 9. Nxe4 O-O {this structure is
tiny better for White. Black's position is passive but very solid. Such
structure we can find in many positions from Caro-Kann and Scandinavian Defense
} 10. c3 {White is protecting the "d4" pawn and is preparing to start actions
on the queenside by means of Qb3.} Re8 11. Nxf6+ Bxf6 12. h3 Bh5 (12... Bxf3 $5
13. Bxf3 Bg5 {Black has nothing to worry about if he manages to exchange the
bishops. The arising position probably seems tiny better for White. But in
practice, Black successfully manages to defend such positions and even can
play for a win.}) 13. Qb3 Qb6 14. Nd2 $1 {A maneuver that is worth remembering.
The knight is heading to "d6"} e5 $6 {Aronian tries to use the slight
miscoordination in White's position, but this is premature.} 15. d5 Qc7 16. d6
Qb8 17. Ne4 $16 {With such pawn on "d6", Radjabov easily converts his
advantage to a full point.} Bd8 18. Be3 Bb6 19. h4 h6 20. Bh3 Qd8 21. Bxh6 Nc5
22. Nxc5 Qxd6 23. Nd7 Qxh6 24. Nxb6 axb6 25. Qxb6 Bf3 26. Qe3 Qh5 27. Bg2 Bxg2
28. Kxg2 Ra4 29. Qg5 Qxg5 30. hxg5 Kh7 31. a3 Kg6 32. Rad1 Re6 33. Rd7 b5 34.
Red1 Rc4 35. Rc7 e4 36. Rdd7 e3 37. fxe3 Rxe3 38. Rxf7 Rg4 39. Rxg7+ Kh5 40.
Rh7+ Kg6 41. Rcg7+ Kf5 42. Rf7+ Kg6 43. Rhg7+ Kh5 44. Rf3 Re2+ 45. Kh3 Rxg5 46.
g4+ Kh6 47. Rxg5 Kxg5 48. b3 Kg6 49. Kg3 Ra2 50. Kf4 Rxa3 51. b4 Kf7 52. Ke5+
Ke7 53. Rh3 Kd7 54. g5 Ra1 55. Rh7+ Ke8 56. Rc7 1-0

