{[%evp 0,52,40,12,12,-7,12,9,33,3,4,-5,20,20,15,12,13,2,4,9,0,0,17,-10,-10,-10,
34,10,42,38,30,6,6,36,50,-24,-22,1,-16,-24,-33,-25,37,41,44,45,48,35,35,31,31,
29,24,-160,-158]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bg4 {The Georgian GM Baadur Jobava
is a very creative player and I recommend to all of you to investigate his
games. I decide to add this game to the lecture because it shows an
interesting plan for Black.} 4. h3 Bxf3 {Exchanging a bishop for a knight is
the most way to create imbalance and to play for a win with the Black pieces.}
5. Bxf3 e6 6. O-O Nd7 7. d3 h5 {Remember this idea. After exchanging the
knight on f3, White's kingside is without too many defenders, and this move is
very unpleasant to meet. Remember that we are playing it with the knight on
"g8". In many cases, the knight can go to "e7"} 8. e4 (8. h4 {is well met by}
Be7 {The threat 9...g5 is so unpleasant that my computer's first line is weird}
9. Qd2 {I can't believe that this is the right way to play chess. Black should
be at least fine.}) 8... dxe4 $5 {An important rule is that when you have a
knight against the bishop, you should try to determine the pawn structure.} 9.
dxe4 h4 $1 10. g4 Ne7 {Of course, the knight is heading to g6.} 11. a4 Ng6 12.
Bg2 e5 {The computer is not impressed, but I quite like Black's position.
Jobava's play is quite easy to understand. Now his goal is to exchange
dark-squared bishops and to use the weak squares.} 13. Nd2 Nc5 14. Nc4 Ne6 15.
Be3 Qc7 16. Qd2 Rd8 17. Qc3 Bc5 {Finally, Jobava manages to exchange the
bishops.} 18. Bxc5 Nxc5 19. Qe3 Rd4 20. b3 Nf4 21. c3 Rxc4 $1 22. bxc4 Qa5 {
This position deserves a diagram in a book about strategy. Black dominates
over the dark squares.} 23. Rfd1 O-O 24. Rd6 g5 {Probably it was better to
play something more flexible} 25. Bf1 Kg7 26. Be2 $4 {a blunder ruined such a
great game. It would be interesting to see how Jobava would proceed after some
natural move like:} (26. Ra2) 26... Qxc3 {Black is losing material} 0-1

