{[%evp 0,35,31,23,15,-21,25,-20,8,-28,1,2,10,-5,30,31,43,39,39,19,21,15,73,107,
154,92,92,135,216,206,210,209,250,222,505,495,619,702] It is time to show you
one of my games. I played Reti Opening a lot throught my carreer with decent
results.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 {I always prefer to play the systems with early c4}
c6 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 Bf5 5. cxd5 {I was inspired to play this move by Mihail
Marin and his wonderful books about 1.c4.} cxd5 6. Qb3 {This is a common idea.
When Black's bishop leaves c8 square, we attack the pawn on b7.} Qc7 {After
this move White has a very easy play. He should follow with d3, Bf4, Nc3, Rc1,
etc...} (6... Qb6 {This was considered the main move for a long time, but I
quite like the endgame after:} 7. Qxb6 (7. Nc3 {Is also quite playable} Qxb3 8.
axb3 Nc6 9. d3 e6 10. Be3 a6 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 Nd7 13. e4 dxe4 14. dxe4 Bg6
15. O-O {1-0 (32) Georgiev,K (2649)-Kasimdzhanov,R (2690) Khanty-Mansiysk 2007}
) 7... axb6 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. d3 e6 10. Nb5 Bb4+ 11. Bd2 Bxd2+ 12. Kxd2 $14 {
White enjoys tine but a long-term advantage. 1-0 (24) Pantsulaia,L (2553)
-Spata,G (2290) Chess.com INT 2021}) (6... Nc6 $3 {The problem of this line is
this pawn sacrifice. When I saw this move for the first time, I immediately
realized that it is time to change something in this line.} 7. Qxb7 Bd7 8. Qb3
e5 9. d3 Rb8 10. Qd1 Bb4+ {Look at this position, I don't know about you, but
I enjoy playing such positions with Black pieces. If you are a fan of pawn
grabbing, then you can choose White, but my preferences are for Black here.}
11. Nfd2 Qc8 12. Nc3 Bh3 13. O-O h5 {Playing on the hall board. Fantastic game
by Saric.} 14. Nxd5 h4 15. Nc7+ Qxc7 16. Bxh3 hxg3 17. Kg2 gxf2 18. Ne4 Nxe4
19. dxe4 Nd4 20. Bg5 Qc6 21. Qd3 Qg6 22. Qg3 Qxe4+ 23. Kxf2 Bc5 24. Be3 Nf5 {
A crushing victory for the Croatian GM 0-1 (24) Khismatullin,D (2609)-Saric,I 
(2650) Gjakova 2016} 25. Rad1) 7. Nc3 e6 8. d3 Nc6 9. Bf4 Qd7 10. O-O a6 {
Black lose even more time and now I have time for the typical break in the
center.} 11. e4 $1 {The main idea is to open the d-file and the long diagonal.
Black can take the pawn, but it is quite risky.} Bg4 (11... dxe4 12. dxe4 Nxe4
13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe4 Nc6 16. Rfd1 $18) 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. Bxe5 d4
14. Na4 Qb5 15. Nb6 Rd8 16. Bc7 {game over. I won an exchange and the game.}
Bb4 17. a4 Qc6 18. Bxd8 1-0

