{[%evp 0,39,45,12,12,3,26,-9,17,-21,-13,-18,30,30,16,16,16,16,20,-33,77,52,59,
68,68,92,92,91,124,80,168,168,162,162,174,166,227,259,305,313,470,441]} 1. Nf3
d5 2. c4 c6 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 dxc4 {In my opinion, the most principled
variation. I always preferred to play this position for White. Usually, White
has a choice between sacrificing a pawn long-term or trying to take the pawn
back.} 5. O-O b5 {First, we will examine the most principled reaction for
Black: to defend the pawn. Now White has no choice and should try to play for
an initiative.} 6. a4 Bb7 7. d3 {This move changes everything. I believe White
is on the driving seat in this line and we are not going to see 5...b5 very
often.} (7. b3 {was the old theory} b4 8. bxc4 c5 {the position is quite
acceptable for Black.}) 7... cxd3 8. Ne5 {The point of White's idea} Qc7 (8...
a6 9. Qxd3 (9. Nc3 e6 10. axb5 axb5 11. Rxa8 Bxa8 12. Nxb5 $16 {Gareyev won 6
moves later: 1-0 (18) Gareyev,T (2584)-Shetty,A (2431) Philadelphia 2019}) 9...
Qxd3 10. Nxd3 $14 {Even without queens, Black's position is quite unpleasant.
White has an initiative and an easy game. 1-0 (42) Zhigalko,A (2517)-Tsydypov,
Z (2565) Kazan 2021}) 9. Bf4 {developing before everything. In those lines,
White should be ready to sacrifice few pawns.} Nh5 10. axb5 Nxf4 11. gxf4 $18 {
Black could resign here.} f6 ({The main problem is that Black can't play} 11...
cxb5 12. Qb3 {[%cal Rb3f7,Rb3b5]}) 12. bxc6 Nxc6 13. Nxd3 {White's king is
quite much safer and Black can't complete the development. Parham easily
convert his enormous advantage to a full point.} Rd8 14. Nc3 e6 15. Qb3 Be7 16.
Rfc1 Qd7 17. Rd1 Qc8 18. Nb5 a6 19. Na7 Qa8 20. Qxb7 1-0

