{[%evp 0,52,45,12,12,-7,-1,-3,9,9,14,-2,12,-1,-1,-9,19,-1,-11,-3,-9,-9,-13,-13,
-22,-32,-32,-35,-35,-147,-150,-144,-139,-137,-137,-157,-160,-188,-184,-194,
-202,-220,-178,-150,-150,-143,-138,-255,-307,-304,-299,-297,-302,-353,-300]} 1.
Nf3 d5 2. g3 Bg4 3. Bg2 Nd7 {Another tricky move order. Black is fighting
against Ne5.} 4. O-O c6 5. d3 {White has a lot of different tries in this
position. The line with 5.d3 is quite harmless, in my opinion, but some
players like it for White because it keeps all options available. White still
can play with c4, e4, or simply to develop with Nbd2 and b3.} e6 6. b3 Qf6 $1 {
Very tricky idea from Kovalenko; as we already saw from Jobava's game Black
can benefit from keeping the knight on "g8"} 7. c3 {I suppose Azaladze wasn't
very happy to play this move, but what else.} (7. d4 {It seems weird to play
this after 5.d3 and 6.b3 included. Black can probably continue with the same
plan} h5 $5) 7... h5 8. d4 {White's play is not impressive at all. I
understand that White wants to play Nbd2, but why play 7.c3, if you are
playing d4 anyway. Kovalenko immediately feels the weakness of his opponent
and starts an active play.} Be7 {Black is preparing Qg6 and stopping Nh4 in
many lines.} 9. h3 Bxf3 {Kovalenko's favorite approach is to give his bishop
for the knight early in the game.} 10. exf3 h4 {The key move which ruins
White's structure} 11. f4 (11. g4 Bd6 {followed by g5 or Nf8-g6 with full
control of the dark squares.}) 11... Bd6 12. Nd2 Qg6 13. Qg4 Qh7 {Nice
maneuver - Qd8-f6-g6-h7. Now Black is in total control of the position.} 14.
Nf3 Ngf6 15. Ng5 Nxg4 16. Nxh7 Nxf2 $19 {Now it is over and Kovalenko won
without any troubles.} 17. Rxf2 hxg3 18. Re2 Rxh7 19. f5 Nf8 20. c4 O-O-O 21.
Bg5 Rd7 22. cxd5 exd5 23. Bxd5 f6 24. Be6 fxg5 25. Bxd7+ Kxd7 26. Kg2 Rh4 0-1

