{[%evp 0,74,45,12,12,-6,10,10,34,14,24,12,12,18,4,24,25,4,3,6,5,5,16,8,29,16,
16,16,16,16,41,41,45,30,36,25,31,20,39,10,11,15,20,15,26,2,22,0,0,-34,-6,-79,
-89,-92,-51,-51,0,-80,-80,-95,-120,-72,16,3,42,-6,-16,-42,-6,-17,-17,0,-24,-62,
-27,-20,37]} 1. Nf3 d5 2. g3 c6 3. Bg2 Bg4 4. O-O e6 5. c4 Nf6 6. d4 (6. cxd5 {
is not promising White much after:} Bxf3 7. Bxf3 cxd5 {In this symmetrical
structure White's bishop pair is not that strong. Many players tried to play
this for a win, but the practice shows that Black's defensive resources are
pretty high. For those of you who are interested to learn more about this
position, I recommend you the lecture of GM Boris Avrukh from "Online Summer
Camp"}) 6... Nbd7 7. cxd5 {With the knight on d7, this taking makes much more
sense.} exd5 (7... cxd5 {is less accurate now. With the knight on d7, White
enjoys slight initiative on the queenside.}) 8. Nc3 Be7 (8... Bd6 {When the
bishop is on "d6" White should choose another square for the knight.} 9. Nh4
Nb6 10. f3 Be6 11. e4 Be7 12. e5 Nfd7 13. f4 $16 {1-0 (30) Grischuk,A (2771)
-Postny,E (2615) St Petersburg 2018 CBM 187 Extra [Arnau]}) 9. Ng5 $5 {I like
Grishuk's idea even if it is not the only way to handle the position. White's
idea is straightforward; he wants to play f3 and e4 and build a strong center.}
h6 10. Nh3 O-O 11. f3 Bf5 (11... Bxh3 12. Bxh3 Qb6 13. e3 {The engine is
trying to convince me that Black is fine here, but for me it is a clear
advantage}) 12. e4 dxe4 13. fxe4 Bg4 14. Qd2 (14. Qe1 Nb6 15. Be3) 14... Nb6
15. Nf4 Nh5 16. Qf2 (16. Nd1 $1 {[%cal Rd1e3]}) 16... Nxf4 17. Bxf4 Qd7 18. b3
(18. a4 $1) 18... Bh3 {Finally, Grischuk won the game after some complications.
I am not saying that the plan with Ng5 is the only possible way to handle the
position, but in my opinion, it is a wonderful practical idea.} 19. a4 Bxg2 20.
Kxg2 Rad8 21. Rad1 Bb4 22. Na2 Bd6 23. a5 Nc8 24. Be3 Qe6 25. e5 Bc7 26. b4 Ne7
27. Nc3 Nd5 28. Ne4 b6 29. Bd2 f5 30. Nc3 Nxc3 31. Bxc3 Rd5 32. Qf3 bxa5 33.
bxa5 Bxa5 34. Bxa5 Rxa5 35. Rc1 Rd5 36. Rc4 Rfd8 37. Qxf5 Qxf5 38. Rxf5 Rxd4
39. Rxc6 Rd2+ 40. Rf2 Rxf2+ 41. Kxf2 Rd2+ 42. Kf3 Kf7 43. h4 a5 44. Ra6 Ra2 45.
h5 a4 46. Ke4 a3 47. Ra7+ Kg8 48. Kf5 Kh7 49. Ke6 Ra1 50. Ke7 Ra2 51. e6 Ra1
52. g4 Ra2 53. Rd7 Ra1 54. Rd3 a2 55. Rd2 g6 56. Kd7 Rb1 57. Rxa2 Rb7+ 58. Kc6
Rg7 59. Kd6 gxh5 60. gxh5 Rg1 61. e7 Rd1+ 62. Ke6 Re1+ 63. Kf7 Rf1+ 64. Ke8 Kg7
65. Rd2 Kf6 66. Kd7 1-0

