{[%evp 0,84,24,-8,-5,-14,14,-23,-23,-13,-4,-2,11,16,14,14,9,6,8,-4,3,8,-7,0,0,
0,16,-15,19,19,19,6,66,66,79,-42,-49,-68,-12,-12,1,-13,-2,-51,-58,-53,-51,-87,
-47,-156,-193,-193,-130,-130,-130,-130,-113,-333,-126,-122,-116,-119,-111,-105,
-121,-121,-96,-134,-135,-131,-134,-130,-117,-210,-209,-266,-213,-263,-220,-259,
-265,-511,-529,-529,-560,-749,-754]} 1. b3 d5 2. Bb2 {[%csl Re2]} Bg4 3. g3 e6
4. Bg2 Nf6 5. d3 Nbd7 6. Nd2 Bd6 7. Ngf3 O-O 8. O-O {[%cal Rc7c5] With a
strange move order we reach one of the main positions in the Slav Reti. I will
try to explain you all the details and nuances in this position. First let's
check what Black can play here.} c6 {[%csl Rd8][%cal Re6e5,Ra7a5]} (8... a5 $1
{is always useful. We are threatening a4} 9. a3 $1 {[%csl Ra3]} (9. a4 $2 {
[%cal Gc2c4] White's structure is not flexible and c4 is not good anymore.})
9... c6) (8... Re8 {It is possible to try to play without including c7-c6.} 9.
a3 (9. e4 {[%cal Re4d5]}) 9... c6 10. Re1 e5 11. e4 Bh5 {and Black is fine}) (
8... Qe7 $5 {[%cal Rd6a3] This is also a typical plan in such structure. Black
is trying to exchange his dark-squared bishop.} 9. a3 c6 10. Re1 {[%csl Re1,
Re7][%cal Re1e7]} (10. h3 Bh5 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Be5 $5 $11 {again this
typical idea equalizes. 1-0 (70) Nakamura,H (2787)-Kramnik,V (2800) Moscow 2018
}) 10... e5 {[%cal Rd7d8,Re7d8,Rf8e8]} (10... a5 $1 {Kramnik's choice.
Vladimir Borisovich, always like to include a5, a3} 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Be5 $1
13. Qb1 Bxb2 14. Qxb2 Bxf3 15. Nxf3 e5 $11) 11. e4 d4 {[%cal Rd2c4]} (11...
dxe4 12. dxe4 {[%csl Re7]} a5) 12. h3 Bxf3 13. Nxf3 c5 14. Nh4 g6 {[%cal Rb2c1,
Rf2f4,Rb7b5,Rc5c4]} 15. Bc1 Ne8 16. a4 Ng7 17. Bd2 {[%cal Rf2f4,Rf4f5,Rg3g4,
Rg4g5,Rf5f7]} b6 18. Re2 a6 19. Qe1 b5 $13) (8... c5 $6 {Against bishop on g2,
we are not playing c5}) 9. e4 (9. Qe1 {[%cal Re2e5]} Qe7 10. e4 dxe4 11. dxe4
e5 {[%csl Rf3,Rg2] Symmetrical structure White's bishop on g2 is very passive
and we are playing in the centre or on queenside} 12. Nc4 Bb4 (12... Bc7 $2 13.
Ba3 c5 $14) 13. Qe2 (13. c3 Bc5 14. b4 Bb6 15. Nxb6 axb6 {[%cal Rb6b5]}) 13...
b5 14. Ne3 Bxf3 15. Bxf3 g6 {[%cal Re3f5]} 16. a3 Bc5 17. Rfd1 a5 18. a4 b4 19.
Nc4 Rfe8 {0-1 (36) Hou,Y (2652)-Caruana,F (2802) chess.com INT 2017}) (9. c4 {
[%cal Re6e5] Another typical structure} e5 $1 {Against c4 we play e5 with good
position} 10. Re1 {[%cal Re5e4]} (10. cxd5 {Sometimes White allows Black to
have strong centre and then attack it. Such play contains certain risk and I
believe that Black is fine in such structure.} cxd5 {[%csl Rd5,Re5] c5 is a
key square for our knight. We can play e5-e4 or if White played e4 then dxe4
is possible and d5-d4 as well} 11. e4 (11. h3 Bh5) 11... dxe4 (11... d4 12. h3
Bxf3 13. Nxf3 Qe7 (13... a5 {[%cal Rf2f4,Rd7c5,Rd8b6,Rb6a6]})) 12. dxe4 Qe7 $11
) 10... d4 {[%csl Rb2][%cal Rc6c5] We reach Benoni Structure with reversed
colors: Several key points to remember are: The bishop on b2 is very bad, The
square c5 is available for the knight Black's main idea is to push e5-e4 After
e2-e3 Black should always consider dxe3} (10... e4 $1 11. dxe4 dxe4 12. Ng5 e3
$1 13. fxe3 Qe7 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Re7e3,Ra8d8,Rf8e8]} 14. e4 {[%cal Rd6g3]} Bc5+
15. Kh1 Rad8) 11. e3 dxe3 12. Rxe3 Bc5) (9. h3 {is well met by the typical} Bh5
10. e4 dxe4 11. dxe4 Be5) (9. a3 a5 {we always wants to play a5}) (9. Re1 a5
10. a3 Re8 (10... Qe7 11. e4 dxe4 12. dxe4 Be5 {[%csl Rf8] one more time} 13.
c3 a4 (13... Rfd8 14. Qc2 {[%cal Rf3e5,Rd7e5,Re5d3]}) 14. b4 Rfd8) 11. e4) 9...
e5 {Option 3 - Dreev's way to play} (9... a5 $5 {[%cal Ra5a4,Ra4a3,Re4e5]
Option 2} 10. h3 Bxf3 $8 (10... Bh5 $2 11. g4 Bg6 12. e5 $18) 11. Qxf3 a4 {
[%cal Ra4a3,Rb7b5,Rb5b4]} 12. Rab1 axb3 13. axb3 Ra2 14. Qe2 Qb6 {[%csl Ra2]
[%cal Re6e5]} 15. e5 Rxb2 16. Rxb2 Bxe5 17. Ra2 Bxg3 $17 {0-1 (33) Oganian,M  
(2423)-Pantsulaia,L (2597) St Petersburg 2018}) (9... dxe4 10. dxe4 Be5 {
is possible here too}) 10. Qe2 (10. Re1 Re8 {[%cal Rd5d4]} 11. Qe2 a5) 10...
Re8 $1 11. h3 Bh5 {[%csl Re5]} 12. Rfe1 a5 13. a3 {[%cal Rd5e4]} Qb6 {[%csl
Rd5,Re5][%cal Rb3b4,Rc6c5]} 14. g4 Bg6 15. Nh4 Nc5 {[%cal Rc5e6,Re6f4]} 16.
Nxg6 hxg6 17. Rab1 Ne6 $15 {[%cal Re6f4]} 18. Qe3 Bc5 19. Qg3 {[%csl Rb2,Rc5]
It is good to exchange bishops} Bd4 20. c3 Bc5 21. b4 axb4 22. axb4 Bd6 23. d4
Qc7 24. exd5 exd4 25. Qd3 Nf4 26. Qxd4 Ne2+ 27. Rxe2 Rxe2 28. dxc6 bxc6 29. Bf3
Rd8 30. Bxe2 Bh2+ 31. Kg2 Rxd4 32. cxd4 Bd6 33. Bf3 Bxb4 34. Nc4 Nd5 35. Bc1
Bc3 36. Ne5 Bxd4 37. Nc4 Bc5 38. Bd2 Qe7 39. Rc1 Qf6 40. Na5 Qd4 41. Be1 Nf4+
42. Kg3 Nd3 {0-1 (42) Korovin,M (2311)-Dreev,A (2649) Moscow 2018} *

