-29996,-29997,-29998]} 1. c4 c6 2. Nf3 d5 3. g3 Nf6 4. Bg2 dxc4 5. O-O Nbd7 6.
Na3 Nb6 7. Qc2 Be6 {The starting position. White must now decide whether he a)
would like to recover the pawn , b) if he would like to sacrifice it long term
or c) aim for further complications.} 8. Ng5 Bg4 9. Nxc4 {Option c): The
following variation is actually known as a drawing variation. However in what
comes. Nepomniachtchi shows an interesting (though also not a new) idea, which
could revise this evaluation.} Bxe2 10. Ne5 Bh5 (10... Bxf1 $2 {is simply bad,
so that even} 11. Kxf1 $16 {suffices.}) 11. Re1 h6 {This was considered until
now as the move one had to know to get the draw.} (11... Nbd5 $6 12. Bh3 Qb6
13. b4 (13. d4 $142 $16 Rd8 (13... e6 $2 14. Ngxf7 Bxf7 15. Nxf7 Kxf7 16. Bxe6+
Ke8 17. Bxd5+) 14. a4) 13... Rd8 14. Rb1 Nc7 15. d3 Nb5 16. Bb2 Nd4 17. Bxd4
Qxd4 18. b5 c5 19. b6 a6 20. Bg2 Nd7 21. Re4 Qd6 22. Nc4 Qb8 23. Re3 h6 24. Ne4
e6 25. Na5 f5 26. Nd2 Kf7 27. Nxb7 Re8 28. Nc4 f4 29. gxf4 Qxf4 30. Bc6 Rb8 31.
