known mistake, but one which even a lot of strong players have already made.}
12. Bf3 $1 (12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qxc6+ Nbd7 $13) 12... Bg6 (12... Bxf3 13. Nexf7
Qd5 14. Re5 $18) 13. Bxc6+ $1 bxc6 (13... Nbd7 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. Bxb7 $18 Rb8
16. Bd5 Nc5 17. Bc6+ Ncd7 18. d4 Be7 19. Bf4 Rc8 20. d5 e5 21. Ne6 Qa5 22. Rxe5
Ng4 23. Nc7+ Kd8 24. Rxe7 Kxe7 25. Qe2+ {1-0 Amin,B (2699)-Sadhwani,R (2479)/
Douglas 2019/CBM 193}) 14. Qxc6+ Nfd7 15. Ngxf7 Bxf7 16. Nxf7 Qf6 17. Nxh8 $18
e5 18. Qe4 O-O-O 19. d4 Bd6 20. Bg5 Qxg5 21. Qc6+ Bc7 22. Rac1 Nd5 23. Nf7 {
1-0 Basso,P (2322)-Solodovnichenko,Y (2566)/Oslo 2014/ CBM 162 Extra}) 12.
Ngxf7 $1 {This in conjunction with the next move is the plan which could
breathe new life into the line from White's point of view.} Bxf7 13. b4 $1 {
I would not like to offer a final evaluation of this idea. But one thing is
clear: the compensation is very long-lasting. At first the computer is clearly
impressed by the black side, but it changes sides more than once. Also the
results of three correspondence chess games (1 win for White, 2 draws) show
that Black does not have to simply follow the the best variations of the
computer in order to win. On account of the numerous options for both sides,
may I request forbearance since the the following analyses can not claim to be
complete.} a6 {Playing this slow move looks mad. But evidently it does not
work so badly. If White still wants to push through b4-b5, he can only manage
it at the cost of an exchange of rooks.} ({The only classical game so far
continued} 13... Nbd5 14. Bh3 $1 (14. b5 $5 cxb5 15. Qb3 a6 16. Nxf7 Kxf7 17.
Bb2 e6 18. Bh3 Nc7 19. Rac1 (19. Bxe6+ Nxe6 20. Rxe6 Kg6 21. Qc2+ Kf7 22. Qb3
$11) 19... Be7 20. Bxe6+ Kf8 21. Qf3 $13) 14... Nc7 $2 (14... Nxb4 15. Be6 $3
Bh5 (15... Bxe6 16. Qg6+ Bf7 17. Qxf7#) 16. Qb3 (16. Qf5 Qd6 17. Rb1) 16... Qd6
17. Nc4 Qc5 18. d4 Qxd4 19. Qxb4 Qxa1 20. Qxb7 $18) (14... Qb6 15. b5 (15. Nxf7
Kxf7 16. Be6+ Ke8 17. Qg6+ Kd8 {would be a dream for Black: at last he can get
his king to safety.}) 15... Qxb5 (15... Nb4 16. Qb2 (16. Qf5 Qxb5 17. Nxf7 Qxf5
18. Nd6+ Kd8 19. Nf7+ Ke8 20. Nd6+ $11) 16... a5 17. bxc6 bxc6 18. a3 Nbd5 19.
Qc2 $16) 16. Rb1 Nb4 17. Qc3 a5 18. a3 Nbd5 19. Qc2 Qa6 20. Bf5 $16 {and here
according to the computer is the only move which keeps Black more or less
alive.} Bg8 21. Bg6+ Kd8 22. Bd3 Qa7 23. Ng6 $16) 15. Bf5 $1 Qd5 (15... g5 16.
Bg6 $18) 16. Bg6 Bxg6 17. Qxg6+ Kd8 18. Nf7+ Kc8 19. Nxh8 $18 Ne6 20. Qf7 Nd4
21. Qxf8+ Kc7 22. Rxe7+ Kb6 23. Qf7 Nf3+ 24. Kh1 Qd4 25. Rxb7+ Ka6 26. Re7 Ne5
27. Rxe5 Qxe5 28. Qc4+ Kb7 29. Bb2 Qxb2 30. Re1 Nd5 31. Nf7 Qxd2 32. Re6 Nxb4
33. Rd6 Qe1+ 34. Kg2 Re8 35. Rd4 Re7 36. Nd6+ Kc7 37. Qc5 {1-0 Pantsulaia,L  
(2556)-Krishna,C (2334)/Dubai 2013/CBM 153 Extra}) (13... e6 {looks very
sensible in order to complete his development as quickly as possible.} 14. Bh3
$1 {This move is often strong in this complex of positions.} (14. b5 Bd6 15.
bxc6 Qc7 16. Bb2 O-O $17 {and Black would have reached his goal.}) 14... Bxb4
15. Nxf7 (15. Rb1 {tr tr}) 15... Kxf7 16. Bxe6+ Kf8 17. Rb1 Bd6 18. Bb2 $44 h5
19. Qf5 Rh6 20. d3 {White has powerful compensation. All his pieces are
working together well.} Qe7 $2 21. Bc1 Rh8 22. Bg5 Re8 23. Re4 $1 $16) (13...
Qc8 $5 {After a long period of calculation my PC would like to play this move.}
14. b5 (14. a4 $5) 14... cxb5 15. Qb1 Nfd7 (15... a6 16. a4 Nxa4 17. Rxa4 bxa4
18. Bxb7 Rb8 19. Bc6+ Qxc6 20. Qxb8+ Qc8 21. Qxc8#) 16. Nxf7 Kxf7 17. Bh3 $1
Ke8 18. d4 $13 (18. Qxb5 Qc6) (18. Ba3 $5)) 14. a4 $5 (14. Bh3 {has been seen
in two correspondence games.It again threatens Bh3-e6} Qd5 (14... Qd6 15. a4
Nbd7 16. d4 Qxb4 17. Bd2 Qb3 18. Qc1 Nxe5 $2 {This looks wrong.} (18... Qd5 19.
Nxf7 $1 Kxf7 (19... Qxf7 20. Qb1 $1 Ra7 21. Be6 Qh5 22. Ra3 g5 23. Rb3 b5 24.
Qc2 Rc7 25. Ba5 Rc8 26. g4 $1 Nxg4 27. Rh3 $18) 20. Be6+ Qxe6 21. Rxe6 Kxe6 22.
Rb1 $16) (18... Bd5 19. Rb1 Qa2 20. Rb2 Qa3 21. Re3 Qxa4 22. Nxd7 Nxd7 23. Rxb7
$18) (18... Qb6 $5 19. Nxf7 Kxf7 20. Rb1 Qc7 21. Be6+ Ke8 22. Bf4 Qc8 23. Qc2
Kd8 {and Black appears to survive.}) 19. dxe5 Bd5 20. Ra3 (20. exf6 $4 Qf3 $19)
20... Qb6 21. exf6 gxf6 22. Qc2 $16 Kf7 23. Rd3 a5 24. Bf5 h5 25. Rb1 Qa6 26.
Bh7 Rxh7 27. Rxd5 cxd5 28. Qxh7+ {1-0 Albuquerque,W (2341)-Iula,M (1441)/LSS
email 2013/Telechess CBM 167}) 15. Nxf7 Kxf7 16. Bb2 (16. Be6+ Qxe6 17. Rxe6
Kxe6 $15) 16... h5 (16... g5 $142 $5) 17. a4 Rh6 18. a5 Nbd7 19. d4 Ne8 20. Bg2
Qd6 21. Ba3 Kg8 22. Qb3+ Kh8 23. b5 Qb8 24. bxc6 bxc6 25. Qd1 Qb5 26. Bc1 Rf6
27. d5 Rd6 28. Qxh5+ Kg8 29. Qf5 e6 30. Rxe6 {1/2-1/2 Bochev,K (2448)
-Williamson,D (2421)/ICCF email 2018/Corr 2020}) 14... g5 (14... h5 15. a5 Nbd5
16. Bh3 Qd6 17. Ba3 Qb8 18. Nxf7 Kxf7 19. Be6+ Ke8 20. Qg6+ Kd8 21. Rac1 Nc7
22. Rc3 Nxe6 23. Rxe6 Qc8 24. Rd3+ Nd5 25. Qf5 Ke8 26. Qg6+ Kd8 {1/2-1/2 Remis
Fernandez,J (2408)-Marquez Abreu,C (2397)/ ICCF email 2013/Corr 2015}) 15. Ba3
$6 {This appears too slow and moreover fixes too soon the position of the
bishop, which is frequently also required on b2. When criticising, however, it
should be remembered that it was a rapid game.} (15. Rb1 $5) (15. Ra3 $5 Bg7
16. b5 O-O 17. bxc6 Rc8 18. Rc3 $13) 15... Bg7 $2 (15... Rg8 $142 16. b5 axb5
17. axb5 Bd5 $17) 16. Ng6 $2 {This move is an easier one to criticise. b4-b5
with pressore on e7 looks very logical. At the same time the knight is very
important for any attack by White in order to swap off fhe Bf7 and open up the
light squares for the Bg2.} (16. b5 O-O 17. bxc6 Rc8 18. Ng6 $13) 16... Bxg6 $2
(16... Nfd5 $142 {Here too this was - in my opinion - relatively easy to find.
The knight is very stable here and overprotects e7. This justifies the
sacrifice of the exchange as Black has no more worries to have about the light
squares (and thus the position of his king).}) 17. Qxg6+ Kf8 18. b5 $40 Nbd5
